<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Samaranch: Doping Cases Show Pan Am Games Successful in Fighting Drugs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ZAGREB, Croatia, August 8 (Xinhua) -- The latest revelation of
positive doping cases including Cuban star high jumper Javier
Sotomayor showed the Pan Am Games organizers were successful in
fighting drugs, said International Olympic Committee President
Juan Antonio Samaranch on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
The Olympic chief added that the overall image of the Pan Am
Games has not been affected and the event in Winnipeg, Canada, was
"one of the best games in history."
</P>
<P>
"Of course it is a pity (to have the doping cases). But that
shows that the Pan America organizers are really fighting against
the drugs," said Samaranch, who arrived here to attend the opening
ceremony of the Military World Games.
</P>
<P>
"I congratulate the Pan America Games organizers for their
really, really effective fight against doping," he added.
</P>
<P>
World record holder Sotomayor tested positive for cocaine at
the Winnipeg tournament and was stripped of the gold medal.
</P>
<P>
He will be suspended by two years by the IAAF, the world
governing body for track and field. But the high jumper adamantly
denied of any wrongdoing. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
