<DOCNO> XIE19990809.0006 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Liu Joins Waldner in Table Tennis All-time Greats </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
EINDHOVEN, Netherlands, August 8 (Xinhua) -- Liu Guoliang became
the only second man in the world to complete a "Grand Slam" of
Olympic, world championship and World Cup singles titles as he
outlasted fellow Chinese Ma Lin in the dramatic men's world
championship final.
</P>
<P>
The 23-year-old Liu, the Olympic singles-doubles gold medalist and
the 1996 World Cup winner, came from 1-2 down to beat the 19-year-old
teammate, 21-16, 19-21, 19-21, 21-16, 24-22.
</P>
<P>
Only Sweden's Jan-Ove Waldner has won "Grand Slam", but he fell a
victim in the semifinals to Ma Lin's giant-killing spree.
</P>
<P>
With 1-2 down, Liu Guoliang took the fourth set with strong,
consistent forehand smashes and then held his nerves to clinch the
match point after wasting three.
</P>
<P>
Liu's road to the final was easier than Ma's. The world
second-ranked fast attacker had beaten the bygone players including
1993 world champion Jean-Philippe Gatien of France, 1991 world
champion Jorgen Persson of Sweden and dark horse Werner Schlager of
Austria.
</P>
<P>
Ma upset world No. 1 Vladimir Samsonov of Belarus in the fourth
round and subdued current World Cup runner-up Kim Taek Soo of South
Korea in the quarter-finals and outlasted defending champion Waldner
to advance into the final.
</P>
<P>
"I didn't feel sad," said Ma Lin. "I played to my best today and
Liu deserves the title."
</P>
<P>
Ma added that he "felt good" for his role in clearing the road for
his teammate.
</P>
<P>
"I beat the top two European stars as well as Kim Taek Soo, the
world best topspin player in penhold grip," Ma said. "I should feel
happy, shouldn't I?" 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
