<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ethiopia to Privatize 123 State-Owned Enterprises </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ADDIS ABABA, August 8 (Xinhua) -- Some 123 government-owned
enterprises in Ethiopia are to be privatized in the coming three
years, a senior official of the Ethiopian Privatization Agency
(EPA) announced Sunday.
</P>
<P>
The sale of 86 enterprises would be conducted by foreign
consultants and the remainders by the EPA consultants, EPA General
Manager Beshah Azmite told a seminar held in Debre Zeit, about 20
km south of Addis Ababa.
</P>
<P>
The sale of 25 of the 86 enterprises has been completed by
foreign consultants, he said.
</P>
<P>
According to Beshah, small and medium-scale enterprise would be
sold to entrepreneurs on long-term credit basis.
</P>
<P>
Only profit-making enterprises will be incorporated into the
agency's program, he said.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, Assefa Abrha, head of Government Development
Enterprises with the rank of minister, called on entrepreneurs to
actively participate in the country's nation building scheme.
</P>
<P>
He said the government encourages domestic entrepreneurs to be
more involved in the privatization program.
</P>
<P>
The EPA has so far sold 183 government-owned enterprises at
total cost of 2.86 million birr (about 352,200 U.S. dollars).
</P>
</TEXT>
