<DOCNO> XIE19990809.0011 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Singapore's Economy Up 6.7 Percent in 2Q </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, August 8 (Xinhua) -- Prime Minister Goh Chok Tong
said Sunday that Singapore has passed the most serious economic
crisis since 1965 as its economy registered a strong growth of 6.7
percent in the second quarter of this year.
</P>
<P>
Goh also said the economy managed a 3.7 percent growth for the
first half of the year.
</P>
<P>
He said the Ministry of Trade and Industry has revised its GDP
growth forecast for this year upwards to between four and five. In
April the ministry revised its GDP growth forecast for this year
from between minus one to plus one to between zero to two after
the first quarter had seen a 1.2-percent increase in the GDP.
</P>
<P>
Goh made the announcement in his National Day message to mark
the 34th anniversary of his country's independence.
</P>
<P>
Goh said Singaporeans' rational and cohesive response to the
crisis has made a critical contribution to the economic recovery,
referring to the wage cut accepted by all, worker retaining
supported by the whole nation, and efforts made to build long-term
capability, to invest in education and infrastructure and to
liberalize the financial sector.
</P>
<P>
The prime minister also partly attributed the recovery to the
strong U.S. economy, the recovery in the global electronics
industry, the improvement in the regional economies and the return
of confidence to South Korea, Thailand and Malaysia.
</P>
<P>
But he added that the recovery is far from complete, citing the
unemployment rate which is higher than it was before the crisis,
serious concerns about cost competitiveness, ongoing restructuring
in companies' operations, the contracting construction industry
and some financial services which have yet to pick up.
</P>
<P>
He also said that external uncertainties remain and worries and
skepticism over the global and regional economic environment still
exist.
</P>
<P>
Goh called upon the whole nation to press on, look ahead and
prepare for fresh challenges in the new millennium. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
