<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> International Symposium for Chinese Language </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANOVER, Germany, August 8 (Xinhua) -- Aiming at promoting the
Chinese language as a globally accepted speech in the coming
century, and improving skills of teaching the language, the Sixth
International Symposium for Chinese as Foreign Language began here
on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Some 400 linguistic scholars and Chinese language teachers from
33 countries took part in the symposium, which was first ever held
outside China.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese language, the speech of about one fourth people in
the world, will certainly make more contribution to the
civilization of humankind, a senior Chinese official said at the
opening ceremony of the symposium.
</P>
<P>
Under the title of "Chinese Language Teaching for the 21st
Century", the symposium will help the language winning world-wide
acknowledge, said Zhang Baoqing, China's deputy Minister of
Education.
</P>
<P>
But with this aim, he stressed, sweeping reforms, both of the
contents and the teaching skills in Chinese language course, is
urgently needed.
</P>
<P>
"Modern technologies such as the multimedia should be applied
in the teaching of Chinese language," Zhang said.
</P>
<P>
The German host to the symposium, Professor Peter Kupfer at the
University of Mainz, echoed the call for reform by saying a
"practice-directed Chinese language teaching" should be conducted
in future.
</P>
<P>
The internationally growing interests in Chinese language
reflect the growing importance of China, homeland of the speech,
said Kupfer, who is chairman of Germany's Chinese Language
Professional Association.
</P>
<P>
In the fields of economy, trade, culture and science research,
more westerns are trying to learn and use the Chinese language as
an international working language, he said.
</P>
<P>
But to the westerns, there are many obstacles in the way to
master the language. One of them, quoted Kupfer, is the complex
structure of the Chinese characters.
</P>
<P>
"It needs one's lifetime to study the Chinese language," he
said, adding that more simplification is needed, especially in the
international teaching of Chinese language.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
