<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Barak Reiterates Commitment to Implementing Wye </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, August 8 (Xinhua) -- Israeli Prime Minister Ehud
Barak Sunday reiterated commitment to implementing the Wye
Agreement, but also called on the Palestinians to consider
"seriously" the proposed modification of the accord.
</P>
<P>
During the weekly cabinet meeting in Jerusalem, Barak said
that Israel will resume the implementation of the Wye agreement
on September 1.
</P>
<P>
Barak also added that Israel is currently waiting for the
Palestinian response regarding his proposal on Israeli troops'
withdrawals from the West Bank. He expected that the proposal
"will be taken seriously."
</P>
<P>
Israel and the Palestinian National Authority (PNA) signed the
Wye agreement in the United States last October, which requires
Israel to hand over another 13.1 percent of the West Bank.
</P>
<P>
Benjamin Netanyahu, hard-line predecessor of Barak, suspended
the accord after carrying out the first phase of the three-stage
withdrawal, accusing the Palestinians of failing to fulfill their
security commitments.
</P>
<P>
After his assuming office last month, Barak pledged to
implement the second stage of withdrawal, but proposed to combine
the third with the final status talks.
</P>
<P>
However, the PNA insisted that the Palestinians would not
enter final status talks until the honest and complete
implementation of the Wye agreement.
</P>
<P>
The final status talks, which should have started by May 1996,
will deal with the thorniest issues in the Palestinian-Israeli
talks, such as the fate of Jerusalem, borders and refugees.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
