<HEADLINE> Face-to-Face Talks Between Blair and IRA Denied </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, August 8 (Xinhua) -- A spokesman for British Prime
Minister Tony Blair Sunday denied reports that Blair had secret
face-to-face talks with senior members of the Irish Republican
Army (IRA) during last month's peace talks in Belfast.
</P>
<P>
"All the prime minister's contacts with the Republican movement
have been through Sinn Fein," Reuters quoted the spokesman as
saying.
</P>
<P>
The Independent newspaper on Sunday said three members of the
IRA's army council offered at the secret meeting with Blair to
give up all weapons by May 2000.
</P>
<P>
The newspaper said the IRA had passed information through Blair
because it was politically impossible for them to speak directly
to the Ulster Unionists.
</P>
<P>
Sinn Fein, the political wing of IRA, also denied the report,
saying it was "absolutely and categorically not true."
</P>
<P>
"The only people who spoke to Tony Blair and Bertie Ahern (the
Irish prime minister) were long-standing Sinn Fein negotiators,"
said a Sinn Fein spokesman.
</P>
<P>
"There were no private republican negotiations taking place.
Our position in respect of establishing the institutions and
decommissioning are all public, there are no private positions,"
the spokesman added.
</P>
<P>
During last month's talks between Blair, his Irish counterpart
Ahern and the leaders of Northern Ireland's main political
parties, it emerged that Sinn Fein was prepared to guarantee IRA
decommissioning three months after the setting up of an executive
in the province.
</P>
<P>
But the Ulster Unionists refused to sit in a power-sharing
assembly with Sinn Fein until IRA decommissioning had begun.
</P>
<P>
The peace process has since stalled and is pending a review in
September. 
</P>
</TEXT>
