<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Germany Helps Tanzania Eradicate Female </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, August 8 (Xinhua) -- The German government will
donate 8.45 million shillings (about 10,700 U.S. dollars) to help
Tanzania against female genital mutilation.
</P>
<P>
A statement issued by the German embassy in Dar es Salaam
Sunday said that the amount of money will be given to Network
Against Female Genital Mutilation for the purchase of essential
office and training equipment as well as the organization of
seminars.
</P>
<P>
The network is an association of several initiatives and
individuals who are working actively against female genital
mutilation.
</P>
<P>
The association's sensitization and awareness raising programs
are to help people understand the physical, emotional, social and
psychological impacts produced by female genital mutilation.
</P>
<P>
According to a report of the World Health Organization,
Tanzania is  among the 28 African countries still practicing
female circumcision rites. The traditional practice causes
physical sufferings to women, increases maternal mortality and
leads to greater chances of HIV infections.
</P>
<P>
In the traditional belief, women who are not circumcised are
regarded incomplete and cannot get married. During the past
years, the Tanzanian government has made efforts to eliminate
this form of violence against women.  
</P>
</TEXT>
