<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-08 18:31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iran Refutes Saddam's Accusations over War, POWs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, August 8 (Xinhua) -- Iranian Foreign Ministry said
Sunday that Iraqi President Saddam Hussein is trying to
"interpolate historical facts" in a bid to "cover up for his own
defeat and humiliation."
</P>
<P>
Ministry spokesman Hamidreza Assefi was reacting to Saddam's
latest accusation Sunday that Iran tortured and murdered Iraqi
prisoners of war and deceived Baghdad over sheltering military
aircraft during the 1991 Gulf War.
</P>
<P>
Marking the 11th anniversary of the end of Iraq's war with Iran
on Sunday, Saddam blamed Iran for the destructive war from
1980-88, in which some 1 million people from the two sides died.
</P>
<P>
"To compensate and cover up for his own defeat and
humiliation, Saddam Hussein is now trying to interpolate the
written history of the region, and the Iraqi authorities
habitually try to refer to their repetitive setbacks as
victories," Assefi said, quoted by the official Islamic Republic
News Agency.
</P>
<P>
He said "the unfounded statements of the Iraqi president about
his neighbors is not without precedence. It is unfortunate ... he
(Saddam) is still unwilling to abandon his unwise practices in his
relations with other nations."
</P>
<P>
He deplored that the Iraqi president's allegations that Iran
failed to settle the problem of the POWs between the two
countries are against the factual realities.
</P>
<P>
Iraq said it has evidence that 13,000 Iraqis are still held in
Iran while Iran said Iraq still keeps nearly 3,000 of its citizens
in captivity.
</P>
<P>
"Despite preliminary agreements with the Iraqis in the course
of a recent visit to Iraq by an Iranian delegation, the Iraqi side
suddenly backed down on all previous agreements arrived at between
Iran and Iraq and drove the talks to an impasse," Assefi said.
</P>
<P>
"We only hope that the Iraqi government will appreciate the
implications of the situation in Iraq and will turn to logical and
internationally acceptable behavior, and that it will opt for good
neighborly relations with its neighbors and for reducing tension
with them and with the international community," he added.
</P>
<P>
Relations between the two usually hostile neighbors have been
deteriorating despite progress in solving their long-standing
disputes, including the issue of POWs. 
</P>
</TEXT>
