<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Feature: Yulin's Walk of Smile into New Millenium </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, August 8 (Xinhua) -- "The first thing I treasure on my
hike is smile, which communicates better than anything else," said
Zou Yulin, the 44-year-old Chinese hiker on an ever adventure to
walk around the world on foot.
</P>
<P>
Beaming the tenderness of that smile, the well-tanned Yulin
told Xinhua what he had seen along the road with an eye of a
Chinese folk.
</P>
<P>
You do not have to worry about police who might take you for
anything but normal; you just smile from the bottom of your heart
and use gesture or whatever out of your instinct, then you're sure
to get across, Yulin talked about his encounters with the Royal
Canadian Mounted Police (RCMP).
</P>
<P>
An ordinary looking man of 165 cm., the worker of a southwest
China steel factory has walked over 2,000 kilometers in Canada
through two snow-capped mountains and a virgin forest of nearly
200 kilometer.
</P>
<P>
Starting from the western city of Vancouver, the lonely chap
walked through the jungle of Rokey Mountains down to the
provincial capital of Manitoba, the city of Winnipeg.
</P>
<P>
Police followed him once they were informed about a strange
looking man sleeping near a highway. In broken English he had
rushed to learn just before this adventure trip, Yulin told
mounties:"I'm China." He then smiled and pointed to his cap, where
a miniature of the five-starred national red flag was sewn.
</P>
<P>
Mounties are quite friendly and understanding, Yulin recalled,
describing the exchange of heartfelt smiles and gestures: You need
a place of safety for sleep, they suggested.
</P>
<P>
Yulin declined the offer with a "no thanks" smile and a
determined gesture of pointing and looking forward into distance.
Communication is there, without language expertise or more
documents than pieces of news on his world trip -- all in Chinese
and by the Chinese media.
</P>
<P>
Police wished him "a happy journey" or "bon Voyage", perhaps a
bilingual blessing of good luck, he said.
</P>
<P>
The lucky guy, as he called himself, has succeeded in acquiring
the visa into Canada's southern neighbor the United States. So far
so good, the guy said with a sigh of relief after receiving the
visa a few days ago from an understanding U.S. consul, who may
otherwise reject his application on the ground of immigration
suspicion: he has not acquired all the necessary documents or
visas in advance of the trip through a total of 16 countries.
</P>
<P>
Yulin believes in his power of smile from the bottom of heart
of ordinary Chinese people. He likes a comparison of his trip on
foot to that of an ancient-time monk called "Tang Seng", a
character in the Chinese classic "pilgrimage to the West". He may
not have to go through all the ordeals taken by the monk of the
Tang Dynasty in Chinese history, but he's in the hope that his
trip may help enhance understanding and friendship among all the
occidental and Oriental nations his trip is to take him to.
</P>
<P>
He will bid farewell to Canada on Monday and go on with his
planned trip down south into the U.S.A.. His European itinerary
includes U.K., the Netherlands, Belgium, France, Germany,
Switzerland, Italy, Austria, Hungary, Romania, Ukraine, Russia. He
plans to go back to China through Mongolia by the end of 2000, in
completion of his global trip on foot of 32,000 kilometers.
</P>
<P>
Jointly sponsored by the Chinese People's Association for
Friendship with Foreign Countries and the industrial group of
brewery Wu Liang Ye, the trip was launched in the South China city
of Shenzhen on September 4, 1998. So far, he has completed his
trip of over 8,000 kilometers respectively to Hong Kong, South
Korea and Canada. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990809.0024 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Namibian President Vows to Crush Separatist </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, August 8 (Xinhua) -- Namibian President Sam
Nujoma has vowed to crush an armed separatist movement that last
week mounted an assault on government facilities, leaving 16
people dead, South African Press Association reported Sunday.
</P>
<P>
The fighting last Monday in the remote Caprivi Strip in
south-central Africa began when a small group of lightly armed
secessionists attempted to seize the local military base, the
police station and briefly occupied the local offices of the
Namibian Broadcasting Corporation.
</P>
<P>
In addition to the dead, 25 people were wounded, many of them
civilians caught in a cross-fire.
</P>
<P>
"We will combat and destroy the secessionists, and we will do
so without mercy," Nujoma told a rally Saturday in Katima Mulilo,
a town in the Caprivi Strip, which pokes below Angola and Zambia
and above Botswana.
</P>
<P>
Nujoma said his government suspected the secessionists, who
want the Caprivi to break away from Namibia, received backing from
the little-known Barotseland Patriotic Front in Zambia and may
have been supplied arms by the Angolan rebel movement.
</P>
<P>
With the help of Angolan and Zambian authorities, Nujoma said
his government intended to pursue the secessionist group to
wherever it is hiding out.
</P>
<P>
An estimated 300 people detained under the state of emergency
regulations that Nujoma imposed are being held incommunicado at
the Grootfontein military base, 1,000 kilometers west of Katima
Mulilo, as prisoners of war.
</P>
<P>
Namibian security forces have also arrested a number of police
officers attached to the local police station, local civil
servants, as well as three top employees of the local Namibian
Broadcasting Corporation's offices.
</P>
<P>
The detained officers had been using police vehicles to
transport the rebels, and were leaking information to them.
</P>
<P>
The Caprivi Strip is an impoverished area with about 90 percent
 unemployment and is culturally closer to Zambia than Namibia. The
Namibian government has been slow to start development projects
here, leaving many local residents feeling they have been
neglected.
</P>
<P>
Mishake Muyongo, the leader of the separatist movement, said
from Denmark where he has been granted asylum that his movement
would prevail, even though his fighters failed to take the key
installations last Monday.
</P>
<P>
"This is only the beginning," he warned.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
