<HEADLINE> 0808040 Sierra Leone Rebels Free 20 Hostages </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, August 8 (Xinhua) -- Rebels in Sierra Leone Sunday
released 20 of over 30 hostages taken last Wednesday and efforts
are continuing to secure the release of the remaining hostages,
said reports reaching here Sunday.
</P>
<P>
The reports quoted U.N. sources as saying that among the
released were seven U.N. observers, five members of the west
African peace-keeping force of ECOMOG, two journalists and six
Sierra Leonean drivers.
</P>
<P>
The rebel Armed Forces Revolutionary Council (AFRC) led by
Major General Johnny Paul Koroma are still holding about 14
hostages who are mainly U.N. military observers and ECOMOG
soldiers.
</P>
<P>
The more than 30 hostages were part of a group of U.N.
observers, ECOMOG soldiers, journalists and Sierra Leoneans who
were seized by the AFRC in the Okra Hills, about 60 kilometers
east of capital Freetown.
</P>
<P>
The hostages had been trying to persuade the rebel AFRC to
release a large group of women and children abducted in January
this year when the rebels attacked capital Freetown.
</P>
<P>
The rebel AFRC has been demanding food, medicine and the
release of their leader Koroma.
</P>
<P>
Koroma told west media Saturday in Liberia that he had ordered
his fighters to free their captives immediately, adding that he is
a free man.
</P>
<P>
The rebel leader noted that he was making arrangements for
senior commanders of the hostage-takers to travel to Liberia so
that he could brief them fully on the peace agreement signed last
month in Togolese capital of Lome.
</P>
<P>
The rebel leader denied that the rebel movement was divided,
adding "we are still united... the marriage is still intact".
</P>
<P>
Togolese Foreign Minister Joseph Kokou Koffigoh and
representatives of six other west African countries monitoring the
peace agreement on Sierra Leone met in freetown Saturday and urged
the immediate release of the hostages without conditions.
</P>
<P>
Sierra Leonean President Ahmed Tejan Kabbah told journalists
Saturday that the United Nations and foreign relief organizations
should review their policy of refusing assistance to the rebels in
this exceptional case. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
