<DOCNO> XIE19990809.0026 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Nearly Shells Pisa's Leaning Tower, U.S. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, August 8 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. army was on the point of
shelling the Italy's Pisa Leaning Tower in the Second World War,
but a sergeant's indecision gave the command time to change its
mind, a U.S. ex-sergeant claims in his war memoirs.
</P>
<P>
Leon Weckstein, 78, now lives in California with his wife Mimi
but in 1944 was a sergeant in the 363rd U.S. infantry regiment,
Italian news agency Ansa reported.
</P>
<P>
"The part I played in saving the Leaning Tower of Pisa is
verifiable: there are documents of that action and I hope that
some witnesses are still alive," he says in the preface of his
memories book, "Through My Eyes" which was published in U.S.
recently.
</P>
<P>
Weckstein's duties during the campaign were to observe the
enemy through powerful binoculars and direct U.S. artillery fire.
</P>
<P>
In August 1944 his regiment occupied Livorno, about 40 km
southwest of Pisa, and in ten days reached the banks of the river
of Arno at Marina di Pisa, under the enemy fire.
</P>
<P>
"It was 10 o'clock in the evening when the colonel said to me
that the general wanted me to leave at dawn with a radio operator
and went as close as I could to the tower, adding that the Germans
might be using it as an observation post," he wrote in his book.
</P>
<P>
Two artillery batteries were pointed at the world-famous
landmark, while a navy cruiser was ready with its heavy guns.
</P>
<P>
The fate of the Leaning Tower was in the hands of Weckstein and
his radio operator, Charles King. Hidden in an olive grove, the
Sergeant pointed his binoculars and brought the building into
focus.
</P>
<P>
"For an instant I was hypnotized by the grace and elegance of
the architecture. I cursed the enemy who was probably using it to
decimate our troops, " he said in his book.
</P>
<P>
But the heat haze prevented Weckstein from getting a clean
sight of the building. He reckoned the Germans were probably
directing their fire from the tower, but he wasn't sure.
</P>
<P>
Weckstein says he struggled for hours against the temptation to
give the signal to the U.S. guns. In the end he found himself
under such a heavy bombardment that he received radio clearance to
pull back.
</P>
<P>
He was told that the generals have decided to spare the tower
in any case. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990809.0027 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-09 </DATE_TIME>
