<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Three More Pan Am Athletes Test Positive </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WINNIPEG, Canada, August 8 (Xinhua) -- Two Mexican baseball
players and a Cuban weightlifting gold medalist were confirmed to
test positive Sunday, the last day of the 13th Pan Am Games.
</P>
<P>
Roberto Vizcarra Acosta and Hector Javier Ortiz, memebers of
the Mexican baseball team who had already been disqualified after
one player refused to receive a drug test following their loss to
Canada in the bronze-medal game, both tested for Nandrolone.
</P>
<P>
The doping tests of Vizcarra resulted positive on the A and B
samples. Ortiz resulted positive on the A sample, and the Chief de
Mission of the Mexican delegation accepted this result and refused
its right to practice the test on the B sample.
</P>
<P>
In an another announcement, the Pan American Sports
Organization (PASO) Executive Committee decided to withdraw the
gold medal from Cuban weightlifter William Vargas Trujillo, who
also tested positive for Nandrolone.
</P>
<P>
The men's 62kg gold was re-awarded to Barrio Hernandez of
Colombia,the silver medal to Jimenze Lopez of Guatemala, and the
bronze medal to Sakamaki of the United States.
</P>
<P>
Another unidentified weightlifter has also tested positive in
Sample A, and B sample is being analyzed, the PASO medical
commission chief Eduardo de Rose said.
</P>
<P>
There had been three doping case before Sunday, including Cuba'
s high jumping world record holder Javier Sotomayor. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990809.0029 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE>   Another Cuban Weightlifter Tests Positive </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WINNIPEG, Canada, August 8 (Xinhua) -- Another Cuban
weightlifting gold medalist was confirmed here Sunday to test
positive for Nandrolone.
</P>
<P>
Rolando Delgado Nunez, who who the men's 69kg class champion
four days ago, had his gold medal stripped off after his doping
tests resulted positive on the A and B samples, the Pan American
Sports Organization (PASO) Executive Committee announced.
</P>
<P>
The gold medal shall be granted to Jonny Gonzalez of Colombia,
the silver medal to Barbosa Morales, also a Colombian, and the
bronze medal to Alexis Batista of Panama.
</P>
<P>
This is the fourth doping case emerged Sunday and the seventh
from the entire Winnipeg Games.
</P>
<P>
Two Mexican baseball players and a Cuban Weightlifter were
announced to have failed drug tests two hours ago. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990809.0030 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Pan Am Games Rarely Showcase World's Best </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The Games provided relatively weak competition, with many top
athletes passing them over. And the embarrassment of some high-
profile positive drug tests have overshadowed the two-week sports
performances which witnessed one world record broken.
</P>
<P>
Perennial Pan Am powerhouse the United States finishes with the
most golds (106) and the most total medals (295), even without
having sent its top athletes, who are saving themselves for world
championships or major meets in individual sports later this month.
</P>
<P>
Cuba fended off strong challenges from hosts Canada, who pulled
off their best ever Pan Am record with 64 golds, 52 silvers and 80
bronzes to maintain the runner-up status to the American B team on
a 71-40-47 record.
</P>
<P>
Brazil and Argentina tied on gold medal tally, both at 25, but
the former had more silver and bronze medals (101 to 72) to place
fourth.
</P>
<P>
Many of the world's best athletes took a pass on this year's
Games. The professionals in Brazilian and Argentine soccer teams
stayed home. Sprinters Brunny Surin of Canada, Ato Boldon of
Trinidad and world's fastest man Maurice Greene of the United
States went to run for cash in European meets. Donovan Bailey, who
was paid 200,000 Canadian dollars to be the Games spokesman,
refused to run in the marquee 100-meter race.
</P>
<P>
Not surprisingly, the Pan Am athletics competitions had been
second rate, just as most of the other major events. The United
States and Cuba faced off each landing ten golds in hands, Brazil
and Mexico, whose long-distance runners turned in dominating
performances, following behind with seven golds each to their
credit.
</P>
<P>
The only world record-breaking feat took place in the men's
77kg weightlifting event, where Hidalberto Quintero Aranda hoisted
a total of 205.5kg to improve the previous best mark by 0.5kg
margin.
</P>
<P>
At the Pan Am swimming pool, hosts Canada were remarkable. The
32-member team surfaced with a heavy load of 32 medals, of which
13 were gold, three more than their best performances in 1967,
which was also held in Winnipeg, and 1975 Pan Am Games.
</P>
<P>
Jessica Deglau, the 18-year-old butterfly ace, capped the six-
day competition for the host nation, becoming the most decorated
athlete by winning four gold medals and two silver.
</P>
<P>
The second-choice U.S. squad still proved too much for their
American neighbors, taking a lion's share of the gold medals in
cycling (11), shooting (9), wrestling (8) and weightlifting (5).
Cuba maintained their traditional territories in boxing, where
they ruthlessly snared up nine golds, and successfully kept their
edge in gymnastics and fencing, each with 7 golds.
</P>
<P>
Argentina turned out to be the rowing powerforce in the
continent, breaking the surfaces with 7 golds, while the tiny
island country the Bahamas produced the fastest women in the
continent, whose female sprinters emerged victorious both from
women's 100m and 200m.
</P>
<P>
Like the Bahamas, small countries like Suriname (women's 800m),
Bermuda (equestrian) and Netherlands Antilles (men's 70kg karate)
all found something to cheer for as their athletes went all out to
snatch the more precious gold.
</P>
<P>
Although the PASO President Mario Vazquez Rana rated the
Winnipeg Games as "the best organized, the most carefully planned
and carried-out Games", the lack of world-calibre competitions
still can't go unnoticed.
</P>
<P>
And maybe, the Pan Am Games of 1999 will be best remembered as
where the great Cuban world record holder, high jumper Javier
Sotomayor had his fourth Pan Am gold stripped off after testing
positive for cocaine.
</P>
<P>
Winnipeg is also the place where roller-hockey goalie Steve
Vezina betrayed his team and his talent by testing positive for
massive amounts of stimulants and steroids, costing Canada a gold
medal.
</P>
<P>
There have been six doping cases, including three more on the
last day, but Dr. Rana has declared it's a "super clean" Games.
</P>
<P>
"I would rate the doping situation in these Games as below
normal," Dr. Rana said. "We have 3600 athletes tested and only six
positive; it's a very, very clean Games."
</P>
<P>
In the eyes of the Don MacKenzie, president of the Winnipeg
Games, the only problem seem to be the size of the Pan Am Games.
</P>
<P>
Some suggest the Games are too big, too long and they might be
too expensive.
</P>
<P>
"There are way, way too many sports and way too many athletes.
We reduced the events from 435 in Mar del Plata to 330 here. But
the Games should still be smaller."
</P>
<P>
The 1999 Winnipeg Pan Am Games, where more than 5,000 athletes
from 42 countries competed in 41 different sports, are the third
largest Games ever held in the North America outside the Los
Angeles and Atlanta Olympics.
</P>
<P>
When the athletes of the Americas meet in four years in Santo
Domingo, Dominican Republic, the Pan American Games are going to
have no more than 30 sports, the Dominican organizers promise, and
all of them Olympics sports.
</P>
<P>
And that's the way Pan American Games should go. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
