<DOCNO> XIE19990809.0035 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nepali Government to Fully Implement Water Project </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, August 8 (Xinhua) -- Minister for Housing and
Physical Planning Bal Bahadur K.C. said at the House of
Representatives Sunday that the government is working with full
commitment for implementation of the Melamchi Drinking Water
Project.
</P>
<P>
Bal Bahadur K.C. said the government has given high priority to
the economic, technical and managerial aspects of the project in
an effort to complete the project within four years.
</P>
<P>
Immediate and long-term policies have been adopted to resolve
the drinking water problem of Kathmandu, he said, adding that in
view of the decreasing underground water level in the Kathmandu
valley, a project will be launched to collect water from rivers
and rivulets and maintain a balance of the water level.
</P>
<P>
The Melamchi Drinking Water Project was designed to divert 510
million liters of water daily from Melamchi, Yangri and Larke
rivers (which lie in Sidhupalchowk district north-east of
Kathmandu) in three phases and is scheduled to be materialized in
2004. It is viewed as the only option to solve the drinking water
shortage of the Kathmandu Valley.
</P>
<P>
The total cost of the project is 272 million U.S. dollars.
Though some western donors have showed signs to fund the project,
it is still short of the required amount of money. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
