<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Brazil Takes Pan Am Men's Basketball Gold </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WINNIPEG, Canada, August 8 (Xinhua) -- The Brazilian men's
basketball team fought off the American Continental Basketball
Association (CBA) players to capture the gold medal on the last
day of the 13th Pan Am Games on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Brazil scored a 95-78 victory, handily beating the United
States for its 25th gold at the Winnipeg Games.
</P>
<P>
In third place play-off, Puerto Rico thrashed Argentina 87-60
for the bronze medal.
</P>
<P>
Elsewhere in the last-day competitions, the American archery
team made it a sweeping victory in the men's and women's finals as
they saw off Canada 251-226 and Cuba 233-221 respectively to take
a pair of gold medals.
</P>
<P>
In the rhythmic gymnastics, home favorite Emilie Livingston
collected 38.265 points to top the lists while Brazil garnered 38.
431 points to net the group gold.
</P>
<P>
In the water skiing event, the United States struck double gold
as Kristi Johnson clocked 62.00 points for the women's slalom and
F.Krueger chalked up 64.5 to take the men's jump title.
</P>
<P>
The men's tricks gold was claimed by Canadian Jaret Llewellyn,
whose result stood as 105.60 points.
</P>
<P>
In the handball, Brazil forced out a 31-27 win over fiercely-
supported hosts Canada to win gold.
</P>
<P>
The 13th Pan Am Games, where more than 5,000 athletes from 42
countries in the Americas competed in 41 different sports, is the
third largest Games ever held in the North America outside the Los
Angeles and Atlanta Olympics.
</P>
<P>
The United States finished atop the medals count with 106 golds,
with Cuba second on 71 and Canada third on 64, as the Winnipeg
Games officially wrapped up Sunday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
