<DOCNO> XIE19990809.0060 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Communist Party Member's Five-Year Struggle Against The Falun Gong( 1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 8 (Xinhua) -- Liu Jinheng, an office worker at
Shenyang Railway Administration's Jinzhou branch in northeast
China's Liaoning Province, has been successful in avoiding the
Falun Gong for the past five years in spite of threats on his life.
</P>
<P>
The 48-year-old Communist Party member began his anti-Falun
Gong struggle in 1994 when the cult was still in its infancy. Out
of curiosity, he had borrowed some books on the Falun Gong only to
find that Li Hongzhi, the founder of the cult, was teaching
superstitions and bragging about himself.
</P>
<P>
Liu later found that some practitioners had died because of
their refusal to take medicines and that others had become distant
from friends after practicing Falun Gong. He managed to persuade
some Falun Gong practitioners to leave the cult and others to give
up the idea of joining the cult by writing articles to expose the
cult.
</P>
<P>
He saw some resemblance between Falun Gong and cults in China
and abroad so he wrote articles in local newspapers to expose the
fallacies of Falun Gong, some of whose followers threatened to
chop off his head.
</P>
<P>
But, his efforts paid off. Some practitioners quit the cult at
Liu's persuasion and his work won the support of local Party
committees and colleagues and quite a number of people began to
rally around him to fight Falun Gong's fallacious teachings.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990809.0061 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Citizens in Shenzhen Earning More Money </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 9 (Xinhua) -- People in the south China city of
Shenzhen, the first special economic zone, continued to enjoy the
highest income among the 35 major Chinese cities, according to the
National Bureau of Statistics.
</P>
<P>
Statistics released by the bureau show that the per-capita
monthly income in this boom town hit 1,502 yuan in April, and the
per-capita disposable income reached 1,492 yuan while the city's
per-capita living expenditure stood high at 1,076 yuan.
</P>
<P>
The city was followed by Guangzhou and Shanghai in per-capita
monthly income and disposable income. The per-capita monthly
income in Guangzhou was 965 yuan and that of Shanghai was 814 yuan.
</P>
<P>
The average per-capita monthly income of 35 major Chinese
cities stood at 580 yuan, with the per-capita monthly disposable
income at 575 yuan and per-capita living expenditure at 472 yuan.
</P>
</TEXT>
