<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Launches Campaign to Catch Fake Medicines </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 9 (Xinhua) -- China's State Drug Administration
(SDA) has launched a new campaign to crack down on the production
and trading of fake and substandard medicines.
</P>
<P>
The SDA issued a circular over the weekend asking local
branches to tighten up inspection of producers and traders of
medicines, the country's English-language newspaper China Daily
reported today.
</P>
<P>
Any units involved in manufacturing or selling fake and
substandard medicines will be severely punished according to
relevant laws, the circular stressed.
</P>
<P>
In the eight months from last August, the SDA received 160
reports on the quality of medicines. Through these, the
administration discovered 32 cases in which fake and substandard
medicines were manufactured or sold.
</P>
<P>
Twenty-five factories have had their production licenses for 19
types of medicines revoked and 35 enterprises have been punished
for producing fake medicines, the paper said.
</P>
<P>
In another development, the SDA introduced a revised guideline
on pharmaceutical production this month -- "good manufacturing
practice" (GMP)-- in order to improve medicine quality.
</P>
<P>
GMP lays down standards for every pharmaceutical manufacturing
process in order to reduce contamination or errors during
production to the minimum.
</P>
<P>
China adopted the system in the early 1980s, issuing a GMP
standard in 1988 and revising it twice since then in accordance
with Chinese conditions. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
