<HEADLINE> Weekly Highlights of China's Trade News </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 9 (Xinhua) -- Highlights of major trade news in
China between August 2-8:
</P>
<P>
-- China National Petroleum (Group) Corp. (CNPC) will further
solicit overseas capital for some projects regarding oil
exploration, refining and pipe laying.
</P>
<P>
-- China will continue its drive to open up to the outside
world whether it joins the World Trade Organization (WTO) now or
in the future, China's trade minister has said.
</P>
<P>
-- The People's Bank of China (PBOC) and the Ministry of
Foreign Trade and Economic Cooperation (MOFTEC) jointly issued
guidelines last Tuesday encouraging banks to support Chinese
business development overseas.
</P>
<P>
-- Exports of Chinese machinery and electronic products grew 9.
7 percent to 33.26 billion U.S. dollars in the first half of this
year, according to the latest statistics released by the General
Administration of Customs.
</P>
<P>
-- China's exports are likely to see a positive growth of more
than 5 percent next year, an official with the State Development
Planning Commission (SDPC) said.
</P>
<P>
-- Foreign banks are now allowed to handle Chinese yuan-based
business in China's Jiangsu, Zhejiang, Guangdong and Hunan
provinces, and the Guangxi Zhuang Autonomous Region, a spokesman
with the Shanghai Branch of the People's Bank of China, the
country's central bank, announced in Shanghai last Thursday.
</P>
<P>
-- China hopes that the United Nations Development Program (
UNDP) will continue to offer technological assistance on a
universal, neutral and gratuitous basis, Shi Guangsheng, MOFTEC
minister, said in a meeting last Friday with UNDP administrator
Mark Brown in the summer coastal resort of Beidaihe, about 300
kilometers east of Beijing.
</P>
<P>
-- Representative of China and Japan signed several agreements
on a five-year term of cooperation in projects concerning
information technology last Friday.
</P>
<P>
-- Tellabs International Inc., a US-based telecommunications
equipment supplier, announced the establishment of its Shanghai
office last Friday. The company has offices in Beijing and Hong
Kong.
</P>
<P>
-- China's grain exports fell by 41 percent in the first six
months of this year.
</P>
<P>
-- The United Nation Development Program (UNDP) considers China
a tremendous strategic partner and hopes to expand cooperation,
Mark Brown, its administrator, said here Sunday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
