<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Children Yearn for Tasty Popular Science Books: Report </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 9 (Xinhua) -- "But it's too boring!" is
children's normal reaction after their parents have spent hours
selecting a popular science book for them, "China Daily" reported
today.
</P>
<P>
"It is incredibly hard to find a really good popular science
book for my son, as so many of them are just not up to scratch,"
said Si Yan, mother of 12-year-old Wang Tingji.
</P>
<P>
Si said she wants to make her son interested in science. With
his mother's help, Wang began to read picture books describing
simple scientific concepts in kindergarten. "But now he seems to
be losing his taste for science books," Si said.
</P>
<P>
The contents of these books are more or less the same once the
often lucid front cover has been opened. "It makes people wonder
whether the books are not just copies of one another," Si
complained.
</P>
<P>
"Popular science stories written for children should be short
and stimulating," said Liu Daoyuan, an experienced editor of
popular science books for children.
</P>
<P>
However, popular science writers have no real incentive to
reach the required standard, according to Zheng Yanhui, deputy
director of the Youth Professional Committee of the Association of
Chinese Popular Science Writers.
</P>
<P>
The writers are paid according to the length of their work,
usually about 40 yuan (4.8 U.S. dollars) per 1,000 words, Zheng
said.
</P>
<P>
Almost all of these authors write in their spare time. "No one
can make a living by this," he said.
</P>
<P>
"It usually takes them more time to write a popular science
book for children than to write an academic thesis because the
book has to express something difficult in a language that is easy
to understand," Zheng said.
</P>
<P>
Zheng worries that there is lack of successors to write popular
science books for young people, says the paper. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
