<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 10 Hot Spots Detected in South Kalimantan, Indonesia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, August 9 (Xinhua) -- At least 10 hot spots, spread
across five districts, have been pinpointed in South Kalimantan
province, Indonesia, The Jakarta Post reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
"The hot spots have been detected since late in July 1999,"
head of the South Kalimantan Environmental Impact Management Board
Madjedi Aseri said.
</P>
<P>
He said the areas were the site of crops and plantations. All
relevant authorities had been warned to prevent fires from
breaking out.
</P>
<P>
"Regents and mayors here (South Kalimantan) are expected to
increase their levels of alertness, so the potential of fires in
this dry season can be reduced to a minimum," he said.
</P>
<P>
Hot spots had also been reported in West Kalimantan. There are
more than 280 hot spots in the province, and it was feared that
they may cover the area with thick smog.
</P>
<P>
In the meantime, the National Outer Space and Aviation Agency
said satellite images showed 60 hot spots in Kalimantan and six
others in Sumatera.
</P>
<P>
Land clearing for plantations was mostly to blame for the
forest fires.
</P>
<P>
Coordinator of the Indonesian Forest Watch Abnon Nababan said
plantation companies found guilty of slash-and-burn tactics must
be subject to severe punishment instead of fines in order to deter
them.
</P>
<P>
He suggested that the government immediately revoke the
licenses of the delinquent companies to deter them.
</P>
<P>
Based on the result of an observational study, almost none of
the companies has adequate equipment to fight forest and woodland
fires, he was quoted by the Antara News Agency Monday as saying.
</P>
<P>
From mid-1997 until early 1998, approximately 520,000 hectares
of East Kalimantan's 17 million hectares was razed following
serious forest and field fires.
</P>
<P>
In 1997, blazes on Kalimantan and Sumatera swept out of
control, and a huge smoke cloud paralyzed the region. The
Association of Southeast Asian Nations has intensified its
monitoring of the situation through its Regional Haze Action Plan
Coordinating Support Unit, considering the growing recurrence of
the disaster. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
