<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Summer Holidays, Spur for Divorce in Italy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, August 8 (Xinhua) -- Far from bringing Italian couples
closer together, summer holidays are often the spur for divorce,
according to a survey released here Sunday.
</P>
<P>
In the survey, 100 Italian divorce lawyers looked back at some
2,000 cases of divorce. In over half of those cases, 52 percent,
the decision to file for divorce was taken during the annual
holiday.
</P>
<P>
Close proximity for a long time to an already half-estranged
spouse appeared to act as a catalyst for action, magnifying his or
her perceived faults, the lawyers said.
</P>
<P>
In 69 percent of the cases women filed for divorce, and in 31
percent men did it.
</P>
<P>
Of the reasons women gave for divorce, 26 percent said their
husbands' defects -- slovenliness, lack of personal hygiene,
aggressiveness -- had been "amplified out of all proportion."
</P>
<P>
Another 23 percent complained their husbands' high-handed and
intolerant behavior increased while on holiday, while 18 percent
were exasperated by his unwillingness to share household tasks.
</P>
<P>
Italian husbands had their reasons too. About 27 percent said
they were fed up with "hysterical fits of jealousy"; 21 percent
said their wives were "incapable of meeting my increased sexual
appetite"; and 11 percent said they made their decision because "
the gap between the attractiveness of their wives and that of
other women became glaring in the summertime."
</P>
<P>
The lawyers said a divorce decision is often taken in the
summer because problems that have been bubbling under all year
come to a head, while the self-control and inhibition of workaday
lives falls away in a welter of aggression and mutual
recrimination. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
