<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Monkeys Reappear In China's Three Gorges Area </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YICHANG, August 9 (Xinhua)-- Monkeys have come back to the
Three Gorges area after a more than 20-year absence thanks to
environmental protection efforts.
</P>
<P>
Monkeys jumping around the Three Gorges area was a scene
admiringly described by generations of Chinese poets, but the
extensive logging and quarrying of the 1960s and 1970s pushed them
to the verge of extinction in the scenic region.
</P>
<P>
Since the end of 1980s, however, the area started getting more
environmental protection and forested areas were closed off to the
outside world so the monkeys began to return to their ancestral
home.
</P>
<P>
Three years ago, farmers in the area set aside some farmland
for corn, sweet potatoes, and peanuts for the monkeys. During
wintertime, corn is scattered about in places where the monkeys
gather.
</P>
<P>
In Niuzhaping on the southern bank of Xiling Gorge, one of the
Three Gorges, as many as 300 monkeys can be seen at one time.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
