<DOCNO> XIE19990809.0080 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Unlicensed, Unlabeled Food to Be Banned in Cambodia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PHNOM PENH, August 9 (Xinhua) -- Cambodia's Ministry of
Commerce has issued a directive to ban the sale of unlabeled and
improperly labeled food, in order to secure the safety of food and
people's health.
</P>
<P>
The directive signed on August 2 by Commerce Minister Cham
Prasidh requires retailers to sell only processed food products
with a label that displays nutritional information, an expiration
date and other manufacturer's information. Improperly labeled food
will be confiscated and destroyed, the directive read.
</P>
<P>
The directive, slated to go into effect on October 1, applies
to both imported and locally manufactured products, according to
Monday's Cambodia Daily.
</P>
<P>
Manufacturers, importers and retailers have two months to
tackle the problem of potentially dangerous food before the
directive becomes effective.
</P>
<P>
In the last two months, the Commerce Ministry and the Ministry
of Industry conducted an intensive investigation of local markets
and found various counterfeit products, most of which did not have
proper labels or were produced by unlicensed manufacturers.
</P>
<P>
According to investigators, many brands of vinegar contained
poisonous elements, and only two types of vinegar are produced by
licensed manufacturers.
</P>
<P>
It is believed that with the implementation of the directive
and the joint actions of the two ministries, the quality control
over food products will be enhanced soon in Cambodia. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
