<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nagasaki Commemorates 54th Anniversary of Atomic Bombing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, August 9 (Xinhua) -- The Japanese city of Nagasaki on
Monday marked the 54th anniversary of the atomic bombing of the
city in 1945, vowing to make new efforts to create a peaceful
world free of nuclear weapons.
</P>
<P>
Some 4,000 participants, including atomic-bomb survivors,
bereaved family members and dignitaries, attended the annual Peace
Memorial Ceremony at Nagasaki's Peace Park.
</P>
<P>
Japanese Health and Welfare Minister Sohei Miyashita attended
the ceremony on behalf of Prime Minister Keizo Obuchi, who did not
go to Nagasaki because of parliamentary commitments.
</P>
<P>
Nagasaki Mayor Itcho Ito presented a new list of 2,733 atomic
bomb victims whose deaths have been confirmed since August 1 last
year, bringing the total number of deaths from the bombing to 121,
588.
</P>
<P>
At 11:02 a.m., the time the bomb exploded 500 meters above the
port city more than half a century ago, Nagasaki citizens offered
a minute of silent prayer, while bells of churches and Buddhist
temples resounded through the southwestern Japan city.
</P>
<P>
Ito delivered a peace declaration, urging the Japanese
government to seek a security framework that "does not require a
nuclear umbrella" provided by the United States and saying dynamic
actions taken by non-governmental organizations would lead to
nuclear abolition.
</P>
<P>
He also called on the world's younger generations to "consider
what (they) can do to make the next century one of peace and
prosperity."
</P>
<P>
The mayor, on behalf of the Nagasaki citizens, renewed the
municipal government's determination to make further efforts to
achieve a nuclear-free world.
</P>
<P>
The Health and Welfare Minister read a message from Obuchi,
which emphasized the significance of the resolution adopted by the
U.N. Conference on Disarmament Issues held in Nagasaki last
November.
</P>
<P>
Obuchi pledged in the statement that his government will
actively work toward nuclear abolition.
</P>
<P>
An atomic bomb was dropped on Nagasaki from a U.S. B-29 bomber
on August 9, 1945, killed an estimated 74,000 people and injured
some 75,000 others immediately after.
</P>
<P>
The bombing of Nagasaki, three days after that of Hiroshima,
was followed by Japan's unconditional surrender in World War II
six days later. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990809.0089 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Malaysia's Industrial Production Index Up in First Half 1999 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, August 9 (Xinhua) -- Malaysia's Industrial
Production Index (IPI) for the first six months of 1999 rose 1.9
percent to 148.3 from 145.5 reported in the same period in 1998,
the Statistics Department said Monday.
</P>
<P>
The improvement was mainly attributed to the growth in the
manufacturing and electricity sectors by 3.2 percent and 2.3
percent respectively, the department said in releasing the June
IPI figures here.
</P>
<P>
The IPI in the second quarter of this year went up by 6.2
percent to 154.5 against the index of 145.5 recorded in the same
period a year earlier, and was 8.7 percent higher in comparison
with that of 142.1 reported in the first quarter of this year
mainly attributable to the growth of the manufacturing sector, it
said.
</P>
<P>
The IPI for June alone registered an increase of 8.3 percent to
152.27 compared with 141.0 recorded in the same month of last
year, but was 1.7 percent lower against May 1999, the department
said.
</P>
<P>
The year-on-year increase for June was mainly induced by the
growth in the indices of the manufacturing and electricity sectors
by 12.5 percent and 1.2 percent respectively while the decline in
June's IPI over May was largely attributed to the drop in the
indices of the manufacturing and electricity sectors by 2.1
percent and 2.3 percent respectively, it said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
