<DOCNO> XIE19990809.0091 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Allied Forces in Congo Unlikely to Be Home for </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, August 9 (Xinhua) -- Thousands of the allied troops
defending the government of the Democratic Republic of Congo (DRC)
against the rebels are unlikely to be back home by Christmas as
earlier announced, the daily Herald reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
Allied Task Force Commander Major-General Amoth Chingombe was
quoted as saying in Congolese capital Kinshasa Sunday that the
departure of the troops by the end of the year was now doubtful
because of the failure of the rebels to sign the cease-fire
agreement reached in Lusaka on July 10 by the six countries
directly involved in the Congo conflicts.
</P>
<P>
The main rebel faction, the Congolese Rally for Democracy , or
RCD, headed by Emile IIlunga, and the smaller one headed by Wamba
dia Wamba in Kisangani, has failed to sign the agreement since
July 10 because of internal bickering.
</P>
<P>
The situation has been worsened by the cease-fire violations by
another rebel group, the Movement for Liberation of Congo, led by
Jean Pierre Bemba in the north. Bemba has already announced that
he is going to withdraw his signature.
</P>
<P>
Zimbabwe, Angola, Chad and Namibia deployed troops in the congo
to help Congoleses President Laurent Kabila to fight against the
rebels backed by Rwanda and Uganda.
</P>
<P>
Chingombe said, "The cease-fire is putting itself into effect
but the problem now is that it is one-sided. The rebels and their
allies are taking advantage of the cease-fire to gain ground."
</P>
<P>
He said the cease-fire had been violated 70 times in the last
one month.
</P>
<P>
The rebels had fired at the allied forces' aircraft twice and
attacked troops in Makanza area, about 900 kms north of Kinshasa,
he said, adding that "we will not stand and watch." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
