<HEADLINE> Yeltsin Sacks Stepashin Cabinet, Names New Premier </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, August 9 (Xinhua) -- Russian President Boris Yeltsin on
Monday dismissed the cabinet of Sergei Stepashin and named
Vladimir Putin as the country's acting prime minister.
</P>
<P>
Yeltsin has asked the State Duma, or lower house of parliament,
to confirm Putin as prime minister, the presidential press service
said.
</P>
<P>
Putin, 46, has been relieved from his post of head of the
Federal Security Service, the Itar-Tass news agency reported.
</P>
<P>
He graduated from the law department of the Leningrad State
University in 1975 and began his career with the Foreign
Intelligence Service of the USSR State Security Committee.
</P>
<P>
After a long assignment in Germany, Putin became deputy head
for the International Affairs of the Leningrad State University.
</P>
<P>
Putin served as deputy head of the Kremlin Property Department
in 1996-1997 and head of Kremlin's Chief Control Department in
1997-1998.
</P>
<P>
He was appointed head of the Federal Security Service in July
1998 and secretary of the Security Council in March 1999. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990809.0102 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-09 06:52 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lebanon not Keen on Normalizing Ties with Israel: Speaker </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, August 9 (Xinhua) -- Lebanese House Speaker Nabih
Berri has stressed that regional harmony depends on an
improvement in inter-Arab relations rather than normalization of
ties with Israel.
</P>
<P>
Arabs can never overstep such issues as Jerusalem, the return
of refugees, the return of Lebanon, the Golan and Arab territories
in order to normalize relations with Israel, he told a mass rally
Sunday in Zahrani, just outside the Israeli occupied border zone
in south Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
"We tell Arabs that peace is born from the normalization of
inter-Arab relations and from raising the level of solidarity and
common Arab work, and not from the Arab-Israeli normalization of
relations," Berri said.
</P>
<P>
He conditioned Lebanon's signing a treaty with Israel on a full
and unconditional Israeli withdrawal from Lebanese territories and
from Syria's Golan Heights.
</P>
<P>
Israel set up a self-declared security zone in south Lebanon in
1985 with the claimed aim of protecting its north from Lebanese
guerrillas' cross-border attacks. It caputured the Golan Heights
in the 1967 Middle East war
</P>
<P>
The speaker insisted that Lebanon would continue to support
resistance movements in the country until Israel withdraws its
troops from the occupied territories.
</P>
<P>
Since the establishment of a buffer zone in the border,
Lebanon's resistance movements spearheaded by the Iranian-backed
Hezbollah, or Party of God, have been fighting to oust Israeli
forces out of the country.
</P>
<P>
Berri's remarks came in contrast with the widely optimistic
mood in the region toward the anticipated resumption of the peace
talks under Israel's new Prime Minister Ehud Barak.
</P>
<P>
Barak has promised that he would resume all tracks of the
peace negotiations during his tenure and offered to withdraw
troops from south Lebanon within one year.
</P>
<P>
But, the Lebanese government is suspicious about Israel's
commitment to concluding peace with Arabs based on its experiences
in dealing with the Jewish state. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990809.0103 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Code of Conduct For Ballot in E. Timor Signed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, August 9 (Xinhua) -- The code of conduct for the
August 30 autonomy ballot was signed by U.N. Mission in East Timor
(UNAMET) Chief Ian Martin and representatives of the pro-autonomy
and pro-independence factions in Dili, capital of East Timor, on
Monday.
</P>
<P>
Chairman of the Forum for Unity, Democracy and Justice (FPDK)
and Dili district head Domingos Soares, represented the
pro-autonomy camp while coordinator of the Resistance Council of
East Timor (CNRT) Leandro Isaac, represented the pro-independence
group.
</P>
<P>
The signing of the code was also witnessed by Dili Bishop
Carlos Belo, head of the Government Task Force for the
Implementation of the Direct Ballot in East Timor Agus Tarmidzi
and the East Timor Police Chief Col. Timbul Silaen.
</P>
<P>
According to the Antara News Agency, the code of conduct
guarantees that all participants shall enjoy the fundamental right
to a fair ballot, including the freedom to campaign, and that they
shall respect the right and freedom of all other participants to
campaign and disseminate their political ideas and principles
without fear.
</P>
<P>
It stated that in the campaign, all participants will not be
allowed to carry guns or weapons of any kind to attend political
rallies and public meetings.
</P>
<P>
They will also not be allowed to kill, torture, injure, apply
violence, intimidate or threaten any person in connection with
that person's political beliefs, words, writing or action.
</P>
<P>
They will be barred from using language which threatens or
incites violence in any form against any person or group of
persons.
</P>
<P>
The code also called on the people to respect the freedom of
the press and refrain from harassing or obstructing journalists in
the pursuit of their professional activities.
</P>
<P>
The campaign period starts on Saturday, August 14 and ends on
August 27.
</P>
<P>
During the two-day cooling-off period from August 28 to 29, the
people will not be allowed to hold any campaign, the code said.
</P>
<P>
Martin said the two factions had an extraordinary spirit and
cooperation during the discussion and formulation of the code.
</P>
<P>
"We hope the spirit would continue to make the ballot run well
and peacefully," he added.
</P>
<P>
Soares in his speech said the code is an important element of
the ballot process as it aims to guarantee the implementation of a
fair, just and peaceful vote.
</P>
<P>
Isaac, on the other hand, said the code was made with the full
dedication to secure the implementation of a fair, just and free
campaign.
</P>
<P>
The August ballot will allow the territory's people to choose
whether their homeland should become an autonomous region within
Indonesia or totally independent.
</P>
<P>
The former Portuguese colony of East Timor was integrated into
Indonesia in 1976 in a move never recognized by the U.N., which
still considers Portugal as the administering power of the
territory. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990809.0104 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-09 </DATE_TIME>
