<HEADLINE> Refugees in Kenya Ordered to Register with UNHCR </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, August 9 (Xinhua) -- Kenya has ordered unregistered
foreigners from illegal refugee camps to immediately register with
the U.N. High Commissioner for Refugees (UNHCR) and be relocated,
or be rounded up and face repatriation, mass media reported
Monday.
</P>
<P>
Cabinet Minister Shariff Nassir Sunday warned refugees who hide
 themselves from the authorities and escape detection, saying that
the Kenyan government will catch up with them.
</P>
<P>
"Refugees should come forward before being sought out by
police," Nassir said as he saw off 1,000 Somali refugees at the
port of Mombasa for Kakuma refugee camp in Kenya's Rift Valley
Province.
</P>
<P>
The minister for home affairs, national heritage, culture and
social service said that all refugee camps in Coast Province in
eastern Kenya had been closed more than a year ago, adding that
his government only recognizes the Kakuma and Dadaab refugee camps
in North Eastern Province.
</P>
<P>
Nassir noted that the St. Anne Somali refugee camp in Mombasa
was illegal, saying that the ongoing registration exercise at a
makeshift camp near the Fort Jesus will continue until all
refugees are relocated.
</P>
<P>
The illegal refugee saga in Mombasa started last Monday when
Mombasa District Commissioner Wilfred Legei ordered the closure of
the St. Anne refugee camp hosting some 2,500 Somalis.
</P>
<P>
Work on the relocation of refugees is being assisted by the
NUHCR, with the U.N. agency arranging transport means for the
registered refugees to the Kakuma and Dadaab camps. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
