<HEADLINE> EDS-Updates with background Yeltsin Sacks Stepashin Cabinet, Names New Premier </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, August 9 (Xinhua) -- Russian President Boris Yeltsin on
Monday dismissed the cabinet of Sergei Stepashin and named
Vladimir Putin as the country's acting prime minister.
</P>
<P>
This is the second government sacking this year since former
Prime Minister Yevgeny Primakov lost his job last May.
</P>
<P>
Yeltsin has asked the State Duma, or lower house of parliament,
to confirm Putin as prime minister, the presidential press service
said.
</P>
<P>
Stepashin's ouster is believed to a result of his failure to
effectively stop, or control, the alliance formed last week
between the "Fatherland" movement led by Moscow Mayor Yuri Luzhkov
and the "All Russia" bloc of powerful regional governors.
</P>
<P>
The All Russia-Fatherland alliance would put the Kremlin in
major disadvantage in the parliamentary elections later this year
and the presidential race next June.
</P>
<P>
Putin, 46, has been relieved from his post of head of the
Federal Security Service, the Itar-Tass news agency reported.
</P>
<P>
He graduated from the law department of the Leningrad State
University in 1975 and began his career with the Foreign
Intelligence Service of the USSR State Security Committee.
</P>
<P>
After a long assignment in Germany, Putin became deputy head
for International Affairs of the Leningrad State University.
</P>
<P>
Putin served as deputy head of the Kremlin Property Department
in 1996-1997 and head of Kremlin's Chief Control Department in
1997-1998.
</P>
<P>
He was appointed head of the Federal Security Service in July
1998 and secretary of the Security Council in March 1999.
</P>
<P>
The Moskovskiye Novosti newspaper had earlier speculated that
the State Duma would never approve Putin as prime minister, which
would prompt Yeltsin to dismiss the lower house of parliament and
then quickly resign, leaving Putin as the acting president.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
