<DOCNO> XIE19990809.0110 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Establishes 5-Million-Yuan State Supreme Science Award </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 9 (Xinhua) -- China announced here today that
the establishment of a State Supreme Science and Technology Award
beginning this year, to be given each year to not more than two
scientists of Chinese nationality, and worth 5 million yuan (about
600,000 U.S. dollars) each.
</P>
<P>
Xu Guanhua, Vice Minister of Science and Technology, said at a
press conference that the award will granted to those who have
achieved major breakthroughs on the frontiers of contemporary
science and technology or have made outstanding contributions to
the development of science and technology.
</P>
<P>
He added that those who have been responsible for great
economic returns or social benefits in blazing new trails in
science and technology, in realizing scientific and technological
results, and in industrializing high technology will also be
eligible for the award.
</P>
<P>
The vice minister said that out of the 5 million yuan, 500,000
yuan (about 60,000 U.S. dollars) will go to the individual, with
the rest of the money required to be used as research funds for
any scientific projects the award winner chooses.
</P>
<P>
Xu added that the Chinese State President will sign the award
document and confer it upon the winners each year.
</P>
<P>
In a related development, Xu said the money for first prize of
the State Natural Science Award and State Technical Invention
Award will be raised as of this year from 60,000 yuan ( about 7,
400 U.S. dollars) to 90,000 yuan (about 10,840 U.S. dollars) and
that first prize in the State Science and Technology Advance Award
will also be 90,000 yuan, double the original figure.
</P>
<P>
He said the second prize for the above three awards will also
be increased from 30,000 yuan (about 3,700 U.S. dollars) to 60,000
(about 7,400 U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
The vice minister said he believes that the reform of the State
science awards system will encourage invention, the combining of
scientific research with economic development, and the early
industrialization of high-tech discoveries.
</P>
<P>
As another major step in the State awards system, the number of
State science awards will be reduced by half, to fewer than 400
projects each year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
