<HEADLINE> S. African President Hosts Talks on Congo Peace </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, August 9 (Xinhua) -- South African President
Thabo Mbeki and his counterparts of Uganda, Rwanda and Tanzania
held talks in Pretoria Sunday evening to discuss the situation in
the Democratic Republic of Congo, mass media reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
No details of the talks were given. But observers here said
the presidents surely discussed the fragile cease-fire agreement
reached in Lusaka on July 10 by the six countries directly
involved in the Congo conflict.
</P>
<P>
The alleged bombing in northern Congolese city of Kisangani has
 threatened to bring setbacks to the faltering peace process in
the third largest African country, the observers said.
</P>
<P>
Several African leaders are working hard to persuade the rebels
to sign the cease-fire agreement. One major rebel group, the
Rally for Congolese Democracy, did not sign due to a leadership
dispute from within. Rwanda and Uganda are supporting the rebels
fighting to topple Congolese President Laurent Kabila.
</P>
<P>
South African Foreign Ministry spokesman Daniel Ngoepe said
that Mbeki, Rwandan President Pasteur Bizimungu, Ugandan President
Yoweri Museveni and Tanzanian President Benjamin Mkapa first had
lunch together before the meeting. 
</P>
