<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Labor, Alliance Still Ahead: New Zealand Poll </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WELLINGTON, August 9 (Xinhua) -- The Labor Party, the main
opposition party in New Zealand, and its ally the Alliance hold a
14-seat majority over the ruling National Party and its ally the
ACT if an election were held now, a poll released Monday shows.
</P>
<P>
Just three months out from the general election, the latest
Herald-DigiPoll survey shows the Labor Party was supported by 41.8
percent, dropping three percentage points since the last poll in
May.
</P>
<P>
The Alliance's support rate was 8.9 percent, up one percentage
point over the last poll.
</P>
<P>
The National Party had a support rate of 34.6 percent in the
latest poll, down two percentage points.
</P>
<P>
The ACT's 5.1 percent was just above the threshold required for
allocation of proportional seats under the current voting system
of Mixed Member Proportional (MMP).
</P>
<P>
Based on this poll, taken over one week and completed Sunday,
the Labor Party would win 55 seats in the 120-seat Parliament,
the National Party 46, the Alliance 12 and the ACT seven. That
would give the Labor Party and the Alliance 67 seats between them.
</P>
<P>
Sixty-one seats are required for forming a government.
</P>
<P>
MMP consists of individual elections in single-member electoral
districts plus an allocation of seats to political parties based
on the total votes won nationwide by each party in a separate
party vote. Each party's share of all the seats in Parliament will
closely reflect its share of the nationwide party vote. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990809.0115 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-09 07:31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Turkey Claims 50 PKK Camps in Iran </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, August 9 (Xinhua) -- There are currently about 50 camps
of Kurdish Workers' Party (PKK) in Iran, in which 1,200 PKK rebels
are being trained every year, the local Daily News reported on
Monday.
</P>
<P>
These PKK militants are being brought to the Turkish border by
military planes belonging to Iran, the paper said.
</P>
<P>
Iranian officers are training PKK guerrillas in northern Iraq,
said the paper, adding that Iranian intelligence service Savama
agent Agay Muhammedi is responsible for maintaining coordination
between the PKK camps in Iran and northern Iraq.
</P>
<P>
The paper pointed out that Iran has given 900,000 U.S. dollars
to the PKK from 1995 until now and also given logistic support to
PKK militants.
</P>
<P>
The PKK rebels has also been receiving logistic support from
Iran's Maku-Dambat district which the PKK regards as a storage
area, it said.
</P>
<P>
Meawhile, the paper said that Iran failed to obey an
agreement between Turkey and Iran signed on April 6, 1999 for a
simultaneous and joint operation against the PKK.
</P>
<P>
Ties between Iran and Turkey were strained when Iran claimed
that Turkish warplanes hit an Iranian military post and tents
belonging to Iranian tribesmen on July 18.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that the bombardment had killed five people
and injured 10 others in the Iranian territory.
</P>
<P>
Turkish and Iranian officials are expected to discuss why
Iran had reportedly allowed the PKK militnats to move into the
Iranian territory during a Tuesday meeting in Ankara.
</P>
<P>
The PKK has been waging a separatist war for an
independent Kurdish state in southeastern Turkey since 1984.
Conflicts between the Turkish security forces and the PKK rebels
have claimed over 37,000 lives. 
</P>
</TEXT>
