<HEADLINE> Investors Keen on Zambian Copper Mines </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, August 9 (Xinhua) -- The long awaited privatization of
the Zambia Consolidated Copper Mines (ZCCM) is being monitored
globally with investors keen to see the final disposition of the
mining firm by late 1999 before they invest.
</P>
<P>
Particular interest in the sale of the mining conglomerate was
expressed by the investors from the United States, who watches
closely the developments taking place in Zambia, the Zambia Daily
Mail newspaper reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
According to the paper, U.S. based Pangaea/EMI Securities noted
that the delay to sell ZCCM last year resulted in international
investors losing more than 50 percent of the value of their
investments in the Zambian stock market.
</P>
<P>
As a result of the delay to dispose the the mining
conglomerate, the Zambian currency kwacha also fell by over 60
percent in value, said Eric Postel, director of the group which
has offices in Britain, South Africa, Bangladesh, Turkey and
Zambia and is listed on Lusaka Stock Exchange.
</P>
<P>
Postel said on the live global financial news network program,
Bloomberg, that he has had several meetings with investors willing
to re-invest in Zambia if the remaining mine sales were concluded
this year and good governance prevailed.
</P>
<P>
Bloomberg financial news, which is broadcast live via cable and
internet and reaches the desks of more than 10,000 traders,
brokers and investors around the world, attempted to describe a
number of positive developments taking place in Zambia.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, talks are presently going on between the Zambian
government negotiating team and Anglo-American Corporation and the
South American Chilean based Codelco to finalize the ZCCM sale
deal, the paper said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
