<DOCNO> XIE19990809.0119 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-09 07:41 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UAE Introduces New Rules on Safe Use of Tents </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ABU DHABI, August 9 (Xinhua) -- The government of the United
Arab Emirates (UAE) has imposed strict rules on the use of large
tents for weddings and other big gatherings to ensure the safety
of people.
</P>
<P>
The regulations have been drawn up in the wake of a wedding
tragedy in Saudi Arabia, in which more than 50 people died and
hundreds more injured as fire swept through the tent where
the celebrations were held.
</P>
<P>
Earlier this year, hundreds of people were lucky to escape
with their lives after a fire swept through two huge marquees
housing mobile markets in the outlying districts of Abu Dhabi.
</P>
<P>
The measures, to be applied throughout the UAE, have been
implemented by the Directorate General of Civil Defense (DGCD) at
the Interior Ministry, the Gulf News daily reported on Monday.
</P>
<P>
Tents are widely used in Gulf countries on such occasions as
parties, banquets, outings, exhibitions and weddings, said Gharib
Shaban, an official of the DGCD.
</P>
<P>
"Tents can catch fire easily, and this could result in many
deaths," he said.
</P>
<P>
Some of the tents can accommodate 200 people and others 2,000
at a time, and ignorance could lead to the loss of these lives, he
added.
</P>
<P>
Under the new rules, all traders and hiring companies are
required to only supply tents made of fireproof materials. They
should also be resistant to heavy winds and excessive heat.
</P>
<P>
Qualified staff members are also required to be present where a
tent is being used.
</P>
<P>
"They should be able to swiftly dismantle tents in an
emergency, be able to use firefighting equipments, and know where
the nearest fire-brigade station is and how to contact it," he
said.
</P>
<P>
The regulations will apply not only to tent traders and
dealers, but also to those who use them, even within their own
premises.
</P>
<P>
"Those who fail to comply with the new rules will be dealt
with according to the law," he warned. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
