<HEADLINE> Uganda to Cut Down Staff at Foreign Missions </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, August 9 (Xinhua) -- The Ugandan government has
decided to cut down staff at all its missions abroad and at the
headquarters due to lack of fund.
</P>
<P>
Part of the measure would see some of the missions abroad
reduced in staff size to three people and one of them to one
diplomat, the New Vision newspaper reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
Ugandan Foreign Minister Eriya Kategaya was quoted as saying in
a policy statement to parliament that the ministry had reduced the
number of activities including travel and hosting of receptions.
</P>
<P>
Foreign service officers, as a result of the new policy, will
now be required to leave their families behind while serving
abroad, the report added.
</P>
<P>
The ministry has further addressed the issue of relocation as
well as closing some of the 26 embassies and sell off some of the
buildings.
</P>
<P>
Most of the missions are in deplorable state and require 5.3
billion shillings (four million U.S. dollars) to maintain and
renovate.
</P>
<P>
The ministry has difficulty in paying rent, salaries and
allowances to foreign service workers and owes international and
regional organizations 7.9 billion shillings or six million
dollars. 
</P>
</TEXT>
