<HEADLINE> Zambia to Monitor Imports </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, August 9 (Xinhua) -- Zambia will launch an import
monitoring scheme to ensure that goods imported into the country
are of acceptable standards.
</P>
<P>
Acting director of the Zambia Bureau of Standards Mataa
Mukelabai said that most of the imported goods, particularly
electrical appliances, were of inferior standards and in most
cases imitations.
</P>
<P>
The Post newspaper Monday quoted Mukelabai as saying that some
of the products are fake and may come to you as "Phillips" or
"Tobico" and you think that it is original when in fact it's fake.
</P>
<P>
He said the import monitoring scheme would be working in
liaison with the Zambia Revenue Authority (ZRA) and the government
officials.
</P>
<P>
Mukelabai said a proposal had been sent to the government and
the ZRA which had both endorsed the new measures.
</P>
<P>
"We are going to be working with the ZRA and the government to
ensure that the consumers are protected," he said.
</P>
<P>
"We will be working from the borders and if any item does not
conform with the standards set, then it will be sent back," he
added. 
</P>
