<HEADLINE> Zambian Police Hold 19 Suspected Rebels </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, August 9 (Xinhua) -- Zambian police in Sesheke
bordering Namibia are holding 19 suspected rebels from Namibia,
Angola and Zambia.
</P>
<P>
Both Sesheke police and district council secretary Martin
Mutale confirmed the arrests made last week, Zambia Daily Mail
reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
Police said they are holding them because they did not possess
any form of identity to determine their nationality.
</P>
<P>
Eleven of them are women and most of them are from Angola and
Namibia and others are Zambian women married in Namibia.
</P>
<P>
The suspected rebels were running away from sporadic gunfire
which rocked Caprivi Strip of Namibia last Monday when the
Namibian government forces exchanged gunfire with secessionists in
the narrow strip bordering Botswana, Angola and Zambia.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile Zambian Western province Deputy Minister Michael
Mabenga has warned Zambians especially those of the province not
to be involved in any fighting in Caprivi Strip because Namibia is
a sovereign independent state.
</P>
<P>
He said all peace-loving Zambians should not be involved in
supporting rebel groups against a legitimately elected government.
</P>
<P>
Mabenga said Zambia does not in any way support secession of
Caprivi Strip and condemns those calling for secession. 
