<DOCNO> XIE19990809.0126 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Yeltsin Names Kremlin Darling as New Premier </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, August 9 (Xinhua) -- Russian President Boris Yeltsin on
Monday sacked the cabinet of Prime Minister Sergei Stepashin and
replaced him with Vladimir Putin, director of the powerful Federal
Security Service and secretary of the top advisory Security
Council.
</P>
<P>
Putin's quick ascent from a career intelligence officer to a
Kremlin darling was attributed to his ability to make tough
decisions, his authority with the power structures, and his
loyalty to the Kremlin establishment.
</P>
<P>
Monday's reshuffle is the second government sacking this year
since former Prime Minister Yevgeny Primakov lost his job last May.
</P>
<P>
Yeltsin has asked the State Duma, or lower house of parliament,
to confirm Putin as prime minister, the presidential press service
said.
</P>
<P>
Stepashin, who met Yeltsin and learned of his dismissal early
Monday, described Putin as "a decent, worthy man" and wished him "
luck, just luck."
</P>
<P>
Luck Putin really needs. He is the fifth man to be named
premier by Yeltsin in about a year and a half.
</P>
<P>
Stepashin's ouster is believed to be a result of his failure to
effectively stop, or control, the alliance formed last week
between the "Fatherland" movement led by Moscow Mayor Yuri Luzhkov
and the "All Russia" bloc of powerful regional governors.
</P>
<P>
The All Russia-Fatherland alliance would put the Kremlin in
major disadvantage in the parliamentary elections late this year
and the presidential race next June.
</P>
<P>
Replacing Stepashin with Putin would apparently strengthen the
Kremlin's hand in the upcoming elections.
</P>
<P>
The Moscow News weekly had earlier speculated that the State
Duma would never approve Putin as prime minister, which would
prompt Yeltsin to disband the lower house of parliament and then
quickly resign, leaving Putin as the acting president.
</P>
<P>
Putin graduated from the law department of the Leningrad State
University in 1975 and began his career with the Foreign
Intelligence Service of the Soviet State Security Committee, or
KGB.
</P>
<P>
After a long assignment in Germany, Putin became deputy head
for International Affairs of the Leningrad State University.
</P>
<P>
Putin served as deputy head of the Kremlin Property Department
in 1996-1997 and head of Kremlin's Chief Control Department in
1997-1998.
</P>
<P>
He was appointed head of the Federal Security Service, the main
successor to the KGB, in July 1998 and secretary of the Security
Council in March 1999. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
