<DOCNO> XIE19990809.0130 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Malaysia's Trade with South Countries Grows </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, August 9 (Xinhua) -- Malaysia's trade with South
countries continued to grow steadily last year amid the regional
financial crisis, its International Trade and Industry Minister
Rafidah Aziz said Monday.
</P>
<P>
Malaysia's total trade with South countries rose by 27.7
percent to 90.4 billion ringgit (about 23.8 billion U.S. dollars)
in 1998 from 70.8 billion ringgit (about 18.6 billion dollars) in
1997, she said at the familiarization program for officials of
investment promotion agencies from South-South countries here.
</P>
<P>
During the period under review, Malaysia's exports to South
countries surged 38.7 percent to 54.5 billion ringgit (about 14.3
billion dollars) while its imports from these countries were up
13.9 percent to 35.9 billion ringgit (about 9.4 billion dollars),
she said.
</P>
<P>
Rafidah said Malaysia's total trade with South countries
increased more than four-fold from 20.9 billion ringgit (about
5.5 billion dollars) in 1990 to 90.4 billion ringgit (about 23.8
billion dollars) in 1998.
</P>
<P>
The minister said there was a scope for wider trade between
Malaysia and South countries as many Malaysian products are
already well received in international markets and with the
current depreciated ringgit, there is potential for these
countries to source Malaysian products.
</P>
<P>
Likewise, with the increasing cost of importing products from
developed countries, there are opportunities for South countries
to market their products here, she added.
</P>
<P>
Through the familiarization program, the six consecutive one
organized by the Malaysian Industrial Development Authority,
Malaysia can share its development experiences in the promotion
and coordination of investments and the management of industrial
developments with investment promotion agencies from South
countries, she said.
</P>
<P>
The program this year attracted 67 registered participants from
31 countries of Africa, South America, West Indies, the
Commonwealth of Independent States (CIS), ASEAN, Middle East and
the Pacific Islands.
</P>
<P>
Malaysia remains committed to South-South cooperation based on
the desire to contribute to mutual prosperity, and technical
cooperation will continue to be implemented by Malaysia as a
useful tool to promote South-South cooperation, Rafidah said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
