<HEADLINE> Yeltsin Announces State Duma Election Date </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, August 9 (Xinhua) -- Russian President Boris Yeltsin on
Monday signed a decree announcing December 19 as the date for
elections to the State Duma, or lower house of parliament, the
Kremlin press service said.
</P>
<P>
The announcement of the election date effectively opens the
election campaign and dissipates rumors that Yeltsin could
postpone the parliamentary elections.
</P>
<P>
It came after the dismissal of the cabinet of Prime Minister
Sergei Stepashin and nomination of Vladimir Putin as the new
premier earlier Monday.
</P>
<P>
Stepashin's ouster is believed to a result of his failure to
effectively stop, or control, the alliance formed last week
between the "Fatherland" movement led by Moscow Mayor Yuri Luzhkov
and the "All Russia" bloc of powerful regional governors.
</P>
<P>
The All Russia-Fatherland alliance would put the Kremlin in
major disadvantage in the parliamentary elections and the
presidential race next June.
</P>
<P>
Before his Monday appointment, the 46-year-old Putin has been
serving as heads of the Federal Security Service, the main
successor to the Soviet KGB, and the Security Council, a top
advisory body. 
</P>
</TEXT>
