<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippine Congress Urged to Raise Pay For Govt Workers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Manila, August 9 (Xinhua) -- Philippine President Joseph
Estrada on Monday urged Congress to back the government's plan to
increase pay for more than one million government employees next
year.
</P>
<P>
A presidential statement released here said the
5.2-billion-peso (130 million U.S. dollars) outlay, which is
included in the General Appropriations Act (GAA) of 651 billion
pesos (1.6 billion dollars) next year, has been submitted to
Congress to cover adjustments in the salaries for 821,376 civilian
employees and 263,185 uniformed and military personnel.
</P>
<P>
"These compensation and benefit enhancement measures are
intended to improve the bureaucracy's productivity and
performance," the statement quoted Estrada as saying.
</P>
<P>
"Averaging 10 percent, the salary upgrading will be implemented
during the last four months of 2000," Estrada said in his budget
message to Congress.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the president vowed to make the massive
administration body "lean and more effective." As a result, the
number of government personnel will fall from 1,099,817 this year
to 1,098,775 in 2000, he noted.
</P>
<P>
The steady drop in general overhead expenses would also be
sustained, he said, from a 20.8-percent share of the 1998 budget
to 11.1 percent this year to a lower 10 percent in 2000.
</P>
<P>
Therefore, he explained, the 7.3 percent growth in personal
services expenditure from 1999 to 2000 remains the lowest since
1994 despite salary increases.
</P>
<P>
"By limiting the growth of personal services expenditures, we
would be able to rationalize budgetary costs so that we can
provide more employees benefits and increase funds for our basic
services," he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
