<HEADLINE> China to See Partial Solar Eclipse </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NANJING, August 9 (Xinhua) -- The total solar eclipse on August
11, the last of the millennium, will be partially visible in
western China, according to scientists at the Nanjing Purple
Mountain Observatory under the Chinese Academy of Sciences.
</P>
<P>
The partial eclipse will be visible before sunset in cities
including Hohhot, Xi'an, Kunming, and Urumqi, scientists said.
</P>
<P>
A solar eclipse occurs when the moon travels across the face of
the sun, blocking the view of the sun from the Earth.
</P>
<P>
The August 11 solar eclipse is expected to be visible in whole
or in part to about two billion people around the world.
</P>
<P>
France, Germany, Iran, and India are forecast to be the best
places for seeing the total eclipse.  
</P>
</TEXT>
