<HEADLINE> 6 Kurdish Rebels Killed in Southeastern Turkey </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, August 9 (Xinhua) -- Six rebels of the outlawed
Kurdish Workers' Party (PKK) were killed in military operations
in southeastern Turkey on Sunday, an official statement said on
Monday.
</P>
<P>
The statement, issued by the office of the Emergency of
Regional Rule, said the Turkish security forces wiped out three
PKK rebels in towns of Catak and Ercis of Van province, two in
Varto town of Mus province and one in Dicle town of Diyarbakir
province.
</P>
<P>
The Turkish security forces captured one PKK militant in
the operations in this region, said the statement.
</P>
<P>
However, it added that one soldier of the Turkish security
forces also died in the operations agianst the PKK in the
southeast.
</P>
<P>
It was reproted that the Turkish government had not accepted
the call of imprisoned PKK leader Abdullah Ocalan for his
fellowers to abide by a ceasefire and withdraw from the Turkish
territory."
</P>
<P>
Turkish President Suleyman Demirel has said that "orders such
as 'end the struggle' of 'go on with struggle' will not have
any affect on our resolution to end terror."
</P>
<P>
The PKK has been fighting since 1984 a war for an independent
Kurdish state in southeastern Turkey. Conflicts between the
Turkish government troops and the PKK militants have claimed over
37,000 lives. 
</P>
