<DOCNO> XIE19990809.0149 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Stepashin Ouster Plunges Ruble, Cuts Vacations </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, August 9 (Xinhua) -- Russia's government change Monday
has sent the national currency tumbling to 25.9 rubles to one U.S.
dollar on the currency market and made many politicians to cut
their vacations and rush back to the capital.
</P>
<P>
The ruble closed at 24.8 rubles to one dollar on Friday and
traders had expected it to climb on Monday, Russian media reported.
</P>
<P>
The Prime-Tass news agency quoted a representative from the
Kommertsbank as saying that in spite of the Central Bank's
interference with huge dollar injections "the banks are still
aggressively inclined to buy dollars."
</P>
<P>
"It can be said that the market is dominated by panic," the
representative said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Russian State Duma speaker Gennady Seleznyov is
calling an emergency meeting of parliamentary faction leaders
Monday evening. He is interrupting his vacation near St.
Petersburg for discussions of a letter sent him by Yeltsin
reporting the dismissal of the Cabinet of Sergei Stepashin and
requesting the lower house of parliament's approval of Vladimir
Putin as the country's new prime minister.
</P>
<P>
Seleznyov said that the date for an extraordinary Duma session
for discussions of the president's nomination will be set at the
meeting Monday evening. The Duma is currently in recess.
</P>
<P>
By law, the Duma should do this within one week.
</P>
<P>
Seleznyov refused to comment on the reasons behind the cabinet
dismissal, saying that he does not yet know the details, Interfax
reported.
</P>
<P>
Stepashin's ouster is believed to be a result of his failure to
effectively stop, or control, the alliance formed last week
between the "Fatherland" movement led by Moscow Mayor Yuri Luzhkov
and the "All Russia" bloc of powerful regional governors.
</P>
<P>
The All Russia-Fatherland alliance would put the Kremlin in
major disadvantage in the parliamentary elections late this year
and the presidential race next June.
</P>
<P>
Defense Minister Igor Sergeyev ended his vacation on Monday,
along with numerous heads of departments in his ministry.
</P>
<P>
Foreign Minister Igor Ivanov, who was to start his vacation
Monday, is also expected to return to work, Russian media reported.
</P>
<P>
Stepashin, who met Yeltsin and learned of his ouster earlier
Monday, said the three months he was in office "were not wasted"
and that his cabinet "managed to keep the situation in Russia
under control."
</P>
<P>
At a meeting with cabinet members following his dismissal,
Stepashin said, "There was confidence in us, belief that there is
a civilized, uncorrupted government."
</P>
<P>
He said he realized this during his recent visits to the United
States and Sarajevo, Bosnia, Interfax reported.
</P>
<P>
Stepashin said he "openly expressed my attitude regarding my
dismissal to Boris Yeltsin."
</P>
<P>
"However, that is his right, he is the president, he is the
supreme commander-in-chief," Stepashin said stressing that he was
and will remain with "the president to the end."
</P>
<P>
"I am grateful to this man for bringing me, a boy, into big-
time politics," Stepashin said.
</P>
<P>
He described acting head of government Vladimir Putin as "a
decent, worthy person" and wished him "luck, just luck."
</P>
<P>
And luck Putin needs. The 46-year-old Putin, who headed the
Federal Security Service and the Security Council, is the fifth
man to be appointed prime minister in about one year and a half.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990809.0150 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ugandan Journalists Back After Detainment by Congo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, August 9 (Xinhua) -- Three Ugandan journalists, who
were detained for nine hours over the weekend by the rebels of the
Democratic Republic of Congo (DRC), have been back safe and sound.
</P>
<P>
A source with the government-sponsored New Vision daily told
Xinhua in a telephone interview that Emmy Allio, a journalist who
writes mostly about the Congo war, has been back from Kisangani in
northern Congo.
</P>
<P>
"He is back and will come to work in his office this
afternoon," the source said.
</P>
<P>
"He was held for nine hours by Rwanda-backed rebels of the
Congolese Rally for Democracy (RCD) during the weekend clashes
between the RCD-Goma and Ugandan troops," she added.
</P>
<P>
The New Vision newspaper reported Monday that Emmy Allio,
together with two other Ugandan journalists, were picked up from
their hotel at 9:20 a.m. Saturday soon after the street battle
began.
</P>
<P>
They allegedly went there to cover the planned visit of
Zambian-led regional ministers touring areas controlled by various
rebel groups fighting Kinshasa government.
</P>
<P>
Ugandan military sources were quoted as saying that Ugandan
troops suffer minor causalities during the clashes.
</P>
<P>
The RCD split on May 19 this year into two groups: Wamba dia
Wamba based in Kisangani backed by Uganda and Emile Illunga group
based in Congolese east town of Goma with support from Rwanda.
</P>
<P>
The internal split led to the failure of rebels to sign the
Lusaka cease- fire agreement and cast shadows over the fragile
Congo peace process.
</P>
<P>
Ugandan President Yoweri Museveni and his Rwandan counterpart
Pasteur Bizimungu are in Pretoria at the invitation of South
African President Thabo Mbeki to iron out their differences.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
