<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China to Promote Reproductive Health Service </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 9 (Xinhua) -- China has been cooperating with
the United Nations Population Fund (UNPF) to provide better
reproductive health service to people of fertility age and
youngsters.
</P>
<P>
As a project, the Contraceptive Service Center of the State
Family Planning Committee is cooperating with the UNPF to promote
the sale of contraceptive pills and devices in China.
</P>
<P>
Sales promotions for contraceptives are still a new concept in
China, where pills and other methods of contraception have been
distributed for free among married couples and people of fertility
age, said Zhang Yuqin, deputy director of the State Family
Planning Committee.
</P>
<P>
Zhang said that easy access to contraceptives and their
effectiveness is important for promoting better reproductive
service. Sales of contraceptives can meet the needs of people of
fertility age, and can also prevent the spread of sexually-
transmitted diseases including AIDS.
</P>
<P>
Since the project was launched in November 1998, market
research has been conducted in pilot areas, and enterprises have
been chosen to produce quality condoms.
</P>
<P>
The next step will be to start the promotion of contraceptives
in pilot areas, said Zhang.
</P>
<P>
The United Nations Population Fund has invested 14 million U.S.
dollars in China to run a number of reproductive health and family
planning projects, and these project were expected to conclude by
the end of next year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
