<DOCNO> XIE19990809.0159 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New Philippine Air Terminal to Boost Tourism: President </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, August 9 (Xinhua) -- Philippine President Joseph
Estrada said Monday the opening of the Ninoy Aquino International
Airport (NAIA) Centennial Terminal 2 will boost the tourism
industry and strengthen investors' confidence in the country's
economy.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the inauguration of the new airport facility,
Estrada said the construction of the terminal was part of his
administration's efforts to make air travel in the country
globally competitive and put the nation back on the growth path.
</P>
<P>
The NAIA-2, a V-shaped terminal with a total floor area of
73,000 square meters, will be the new home for the nation's flag
carrier, Philippine Airlines (PAL), to spare more parking space at
the Manila Domestic Airport for other local airlines.
</P>
<P>
The 5.3-billion-peso (130 million U.S. dollars) terminal was
designed to accommodate 9 million passengers annually, or twice
the capacity of the old Manila Domestic Airport.
</P>
<P>
The NAIA-2 terminal will also house a section for international
flights to ease the current congestion at the NAIA-1 terminal.
</P>
<P>
According to the president, the construction of the 65-hectare
NAIA-3 terminal is now in progress and is expected to be completed
in 2001. This terminal will replace the existing international
passenger terminal.
</P>
</TEXT>
