<DOCNO> XIE19990809.0162 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Quality of China-Made Shirts Improves </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 9 (Xinhua) -- The latest survey by the State
Bureau of Quality and Technical Supervision shows that the quality
of shirts produced in China has been improving since early 1990s.
</P>
<P>
The survey, conducted in the second quarter this year, involved
some 171 brands of shirts made by 196 enterprises in Beijing,
Tianjin, Shanghai, Zhejiang Province, and eight other Chinese
regions.
</P>
<P>
It was found that 86.8 percent of the surveyed products, or 145
brands, are of good quality, while the other 26 brands were
determined to be substandard products.
</P>
<P>
A similar survey in 1998 showed that 85.2 percent of the shirts
were of good quality, compared with 68.9 percent in 1996, 74.7
percent in 1993, and 71.9 percent in 1992.
</P>
<P>
The bureau has told major department stores to improve their
quality-control systems, as 25 of the 26 substandard brands can be
found in these stores.
</P>
<P>
According to official figures, China's 3,000-plus shirt
manufacturers produced 1.64 billion shirts in 1998.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990809.0163 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Japan's Parliament Enacts Flag-Anthem Bill </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, August 9 (Xinhua) -- Japan's Diet (parliament) on Monday
enacted a bill to legally recognize the Hinomaru as the country's
national flag and "Kimigayo" as the national anthem.
</P>
<P>
The House of Councilors (upper house) passed the bill in its
plenary session with the support of the Liberal Democratic Party,
its coalition partner the Liberal Party (LP) and the New Komeito
party.
</P>
<P>
The largest opposition Democratic Party of Japan (DPJ)
submitted an alternative bill that would only recognize the
Hinomaru, but the bill was voted down.
</P>
<P>
The law, which will come into force Friday, consists of two
articles, one for the flag and the other the anthem, and has no
clauses obliging the public to show respect for them or
stipulating punishment for not doing so.
</P>
<P>
The Hinomaru (the rising sun) and "Kimigayo," unofficially
translated as "his majesty's reign," have served as Japan's de
facto national symbols since the end of World War II.
</P>
<P>
The question of whether to legally recognize them has been
sensitive because of their links to Japan's Imperial system and
wartime militarism.
</P>
<P>
The Japanese government began studying legislation on the flag
and the anthem in early March, following the suicide February 28
of a high school principal in Hiroshima Prefecture, western Japan.
</P>
<P>
The principal had been ordered by the prefectural board of
education to hoist the flag and have the anthem sung at the school
's graduation ceremony February 29, while teachers at the school
had opposed the idea, especially the singing of "Kimigayo."
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990809.0164 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-09 09:14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Group 77's Asian Ministerial Meeting Convenes in Lebanon </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, August 9 (Xinhua) -- A ministerial meeting of the
Asian member states of the Group 77 opened in Beirut on Monday in
preparations for the United Nations Conference on Trade and
Development (UNCTAD) to be held in 2000.
</P>
<P>
Lebanese Minister of Economy, Trade and Industry Nasser Saidi
said at the opening ceremony that the meeting is the largest
gathering of Asian countries in this century dealing with trade and
development issues.
</P>
<P>
He voiced hope that in the four-day conference, the
participants formulate common strategies and policies for trade
and development to face the challenges of globalization and
liberalization in the new century.
</P>
<P>
Topics on the Asian meeting will include private capital flows
and instability in the development process, debt problems, the
international trading system, information technology, governance
of the globalizing world economy.
</P>
<P>
Some 300 representatives, including more than 10 ministers of
economy and finance from the 44 Asian member states, are attending
the conference.
</P>
<P>
The Group of 77, which now has 133 member states, was
established in 1964 by 77 developing countries at the end of the
first session of the UNCTAD in Geneva.
</P>
<P>
As the largest third world coalition in the U.N., the group
works on promoting the collective interests of the coalition and
its joint capacity on all major international issues in the
U.N. system as well as on promoting economic and technical
cooperation between developing countries.
</P>
<P>
Other regional groups of the Group 77 will also congregate
over the next two months to declare their positions concerning
UNCTAD and to present it to the ministerial meeting of the entire
Group 77 slated for 13-16 September in Marrakech, Morocco.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
