<DOCNO> XIE19990809.0166 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-09 09:19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Turkey to Launch Anti-torture Campaign </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, August 9 (Xinhua) -- The Turkish government has
proposed increased penalties for those who commit torture offenses
in an effort to prevent torture and human rights abuses.
</P>
<P>
The proposal, prepared by Prime Minister Bulent Ecevit's
coalition government, was submitted to a subcommission after it
was debated by the parliament's Justice Commission, the Daily News
reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
The current 57th Turkish government has promised to improve
Turkey's poor human rights record and reform its judicial system,
said the paper.
</P>
<P>
The paper quoted Justice Minister Hikmet Sami Turk as saying
that torture allegations has harmed the image of Turkey on an
international level, adding that although torture is forbidden by
law in Turkey, there are such cases in Turkey like many other
countries.
</P>
<P>
The government wants the parliament to pass the draft amendment
bill which deals with torture crimes in Articles 243, 245 and 364
of Turkey's Penal Code as soon as possible.
</P>
<P>
If a torture case results in the death of a victim, it will be
dealt with "causing death without intent," said the paper. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
