<DOCNO> XIE19990809.0171 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Malaysia Advised Not to Relax Currency Control </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, August 9 (Xinhua) -- Malaysia should not relax
currency controls until its financial system has been
restructured, an Islamic Development Bank official said here
Monday.
</P>
<P>
"My advise to Malaysia is not to do away with exchange
restrictions until the financial market has been restructured to
make it difficult for speculators to play around," Mabid Ali
Al-Jarhi, director of Islamic Development Bank's Islamic research
and training institute told reporters after the opening of the
three-day International Conference On Islamic Economics in the
21st Century.
</P>
<P>
Malaysia imposed the currency controls in early September last
year following the sharp fall of the stock market due to alleged
attacks by speculators.
</P>
<P>
The official described the currency controls as the only way to
resolve problems at the time of financial crisis, but cautioned
that this approach should be lifted after one or two years.
</P>
<P>
Since (currency) control is necessary as the first step, the
second step is to study the market structure, he said, adding that
in this case, policy-makers must study the rules to make it
difficult for speculators to come in as well as minimize the free
flow of funds or "hot money" into the country for the development
of an orderly market.
</P>
<P>
He suggested that in restructuring the capital market, Malaysia
adopt an Islamic financial model that can justify between
investment and economic growth, saying an Islamic financial system
has its investments based on profit sharing, not short-term
speculation. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990809.0172 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-09 </DATE_TIME>
