<HEADLINE> Share Prices Move Higher in Tokyo on Bargain-hunting </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, August 9 (Xinhua) -- Stock prices turned upward in Tokyo
Monday, boosted by bargain-hunting after the key Nikkei index had
lost nearly 890 points during the previous three trading days.
</P>
<P>
The Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selected issues on the First
Section of the Tokyo Stock Exchange rose 106.21 points, or 0.62
percent, from last Friday's close to end at 17,190.45.
</P>
<P>
The broader-based Tokyo Stock Price Index (TOPIX), covering all
First Section issues, added 3.85 points or 0.27 percent to 1,424.
53.
</P>
<P>
Turnover on the major section decreased to 323.16 million
shares from 463.35 million shares last Friday amid the peak of the
Japanese summer holiday season.
</P>
<P>
Nippon Steel Corp. was Monday's volume leader.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. dollar's upturn against the yen prompted investors to
buy back stocks, despite Friday's fall on Wall Street, traders
said.
</P>
<P>
Remarks by Japan's Economic Planning Agency chief Taichi
Sakaiya, who said Sunday the government needed to compile a large-
scale second extra budget for fiscal 1999, also lifted share
prices, they said.
</P>
<P>
Of the issues listed on the First Section, gainers exceeded
losers 670 to 486, with 153 issues remaining unchanged. 
</P>
</TEXT>
