<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indonesian President Warns of Possible Repeat of </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, August 9 (Xinhua) -- Indonesian President B.J. Habibie
Monday warned about a possible repeat of the forest fire disaster
that occurred in 1997.
</P>
<P>
"I have received a report on the forest fires in several areas
in (the islands of) Sumatera and Kalimantan and the smog that has
interrupted the people's activities," Habibie said.
</P>
<P>
While opening the 2nd National Coordination Meeting on
Environmental Management at the state palace here, the president
underscored the importance of readiness for all instances to face
the forest fires and their impacts.
</P>
<P>
He said the relevant ministries and agencies should immediately
coordinate in taking measures to prevent the forest fires from
spreading.
</P>
<P>
"No forest fire should occur again due to our carelessness," he
added.
</P>
<P>
He said a repeat of the 1997 forest fire disaster would harm
the country's environment all the more.
</P>
<P>
"Our time, thoughts and energy would be wasted," he said.
</P>
<P>
Based on data collected by the Indonesian Outerspace and
Aviation Agency, there are 45 hot spots in Riau, 13 in North
Sumatera, nine in South Sumatera, 14 in West Kalimantan and two in
Central Kalimantan.
</P>
<P>
The Association of Southeast Asian Nations (ASEAN) has formed a
team which has begun monitoring the smog that has covered Brunei
Darussalam, Indonesia, Malaysia and Singapore for the past weeks,
the ASEAN Secretariat said in a press statement available here
Monday.
</P>
<P>
In 1997, blazes on Kalimantan and Sumatera spread out of
control, and a huge smoke cloud paralyzed the region. The 1997
fires destroyed about 5 million hectares of forest in the country
with an economic loss of about 4 billion U.S. dollars. 
</P>
</TEXT>
