<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Manila Takes Action to Help Landslide Victims </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, August 9 (Xinhua) -- Philippine President Joseph
Estrada has ordered the Department of Justice to assist residents
of the landslide-hit Cherry Hills subdivision in Antipolo City in
suing the private developer of the housing project.
</P>
<P>
Jesus Remulla, assistant secretary of the presidential
management staff said Monday the president wants to help the
victims recover from the tragedy.
</P>
<P>
Remulla, who heads an inter-agency fact-finding committee
created by the President on August 5, was charged to look into the
causes of the tragedy and pinpoint those responsible for it.
</P>
<P>
In his report to the President, Remulla said the developer of
the Cherry Hills subdivision, along with several government
agencies involved in issuing permits and clearances to the
project, could be held criminally, civilly and administratively
liable for the tragedy which occurred on the night of August 3.
</P>
<P>
The tragedy left scores of people dead and several others
injured and trapped in the rubble caused by the landslide.
</P>
<P>
Remulla said the Justice Department, along with the National
Bureau of Investigation), would also investigate further the
liabilities of government officials and private parties in the
tragedy.
</P>
<P>
"Who signed the permit? Who inspected the project and approved
it? Those who sign the permit are not the ones who actually
inspect the site because they have a staff to do it for them.
Usually they involve high-ranking officials. So this has to be an
integrated probe," he said.
</P>
<P>
Remulla said, the fact-finding agency has recommended the
rationalization of standards in building housing projects and the
designation of one agency to ensure that developers prevent such
tragedies in the future. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
