Liberation:
</P>
<P>
-- Carla del Ponte, the Swiss federal prosecutor, will replace
Louise Arbour as the head of the International Criminal Tribunal
for former Yugoslavia and Rwanda. A specialist in anti-mafia files,
the new iron lady has not hesitated in showing her determination
in fighting organized crimes from South American drug traffickers
to the Russian Mafia.
</P>
<P>
-- Yaguine Koita and Fode Tounkara, the two Guineas teenagers
who froze to death in a landing train of a Belgian plane flying
from Africa to Europe last week, were given almost a state funeral
by the Guineas government in Conakry on Sunday. Many of the
Guineas regard the two youths as "martyrs of Africa" and "
spokesman of Africa to deliver a message" to Europe.
</P>
<P>
Le Figaro:
</P>
<P>
-- The annual manifestation of Corsican nationalists, the
Journees Internationales de Corte, which ended on Sunday, showed
that the Corsican nationalists are far away from giving up
violence against the French government. This year's manifestation
was marked by a reaffirmed support to the men who claimed the
assassination of the former Corsican governor Erignac two years
ago.
</P>
<P>
-- Clashes took place on Saturday and Sunday between the French
peace-keeping forces and Kosovar Albanians, who tried to break
into the Serb enclave in the city of Mitrovica in northern Kosovo.
French soldiers stopped Albanians from marching into the Serb
district of the city, separated from the other part of the city by
a bridge which has become a symbol of hatred between the two
ethnic groups. 
</P>
