<DOCNO> XIE19990809.0185 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ferguson Attacks Football "Greed" </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, August 9 (Xinhua) -- Manchester United manager Sir Alex
Ferguson has attacked greed in football, saying it is tarnishing
the profession.
</P>
<P>
Speaking on BBC One's Breakfast with Frost programme, Ferguson
said spiralling player wages were now "extraordinarily high", with
some earning "unbelievable" amounts.
</P>
<P>
He said: "This thing where greed comes and various other
aspects come out, it does the game no good at all.
</P>
<P>
"We are talking about a small percentage who have let everyone
down, so to speak, they have let their profession down."
</P>
<P>
He sympathised with Arsenal manager Arsene Wenger over the "
kick in the teeth" that was the Nicolas Anelka affair.
</P>
<P>
Anelka has been condemned for quitting Arsenal to join Spanish
club Real Madrid for 23.5 million pounds.
</P>
<P>
Ferguson said selling Anelka must have been a "terribly
difficult decision" for Wenger.
</P>
<P>
The Manchester United manager also ruled out ever taking on the
England manager's job, although he said he wanted to keep an "
active role" in football when his contract ends.
</P>
<P>
But he said he would be "delighted" to get out of management,
especially the media commitments the job entails in the modern era.
</P>
<P>
He even hinted he would consider getting involved in politics
once his football career comes to an end.
</P>
<P>
Asked whether he had ever considered standing for Parliament he
said: "I don't know enough about politics to get involved in that.
"
</P>
<P>
But he added: "I possibly could, because once you take the
challenge of something then it changes your whole perspective of
things."
</P>
<P>
Sir Alex also said he "wouldn't put a penny" on Manchester
United playing in this season's FA Cup.
</P>
<P>
He said the reaction to United's withdrawal from the
competition had "frustrated him" and accused the government and FA
of taking a "back step" after public outcry at the move.
</P>
<P>
The club took what it thought was the "best decision for
English football", he said.
</P>
<P>
The interview came amid reports that Ferguson is to be
questioned by detectives investigating the 40,000 pounds he was
given by a foreign agent, allegedly during the sale of Andrei
Kanchelskis to Everton.
</P>
<P>
The manager said: "The best thing a manager can do now, and
this is going to be very important, is don't get involved in the
money side of it, because I am sure the temptation is going to be
there." 
</P>
</TEXT>
