<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Two Swimmers Banned for Four Years after Positive Tests </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, August 9 (Xinhua) -- Two swimmers from Spain and
Slovenia were banned for four years after positive doping tests,
the sport's world governing body said in Lausanne on Monday.
</P>
<P>
FINA said Spain's David Meca-Medina and Slovenian Igor Majcen
were suspended after both tested positive for the steroid
nandrolone earlier in the season.
</P>
<P>
Meca-Medina, the second-ranked long-distance swimmer in the
world, broke the course record when he won Saturday's 22-mile race
in the Ocean Marathon in Atlantic City, New Jersey, while Majcen
finished third in the same race.
</P>
<P>
The bans are effective from Monday.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, American synchronized diver Tracy Bonner who won the
U.S. championships with her partner Kathy Pesek, was banned for a
year after testing positive for dextroamphetamine.
</P>
<P>
Russia's Yulia Pakhalina, the reigning world and European
champion for 3-meter springboard diving, was banned for two months
after testing positive for caffeine. 
</P>
</TEXT>
