<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nigerian President Approves Troop Deployment in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, August 9 (Xinhua) -- Nigerian President Olusegun
Obasanjo has approved the deployment of soldiers to the riverine
areas of Ondo State following the escalation of the ethnic
conflict between Ijaw-Arogbo and Ugbo-Ilaje communities in the
southeast.
</P>
<P>
Ondo State Governor Chief Adebayo Adefarati said in a broadcast
at the weekend that the measure became necessary because of the
failure of the two parties to respect the peace agreement signed
two days ago, The Punch newspaper reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
"I'm sad to say that the situation has seriously deteriorated
in the past two days," the governor noted, adding that "unless
there is a cease- fire within 24 hours from this time of my
broadcast, the security forces would be deployed as they have been
put on the red alert."
</P>
<P>
The paper said that about 300 people were feared dead since
renewed hostilities broke out in the area two weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
Despite the Nigerian government's warning of armed intervention
in the Ijaw/Ilaje conflict, fresh violence reportedly erupted
between the two communities in the early hours of Sunday, the
paper added.
</P>
<P>
The government's warning was reiterated by General Officer
Commanding 2nd Mechanized Division Major General Ekpo Archibong,
who held a closed door meeting with representatives of the two
communities Saturday.
</P>
<P>
He told the press after the meeting that he was sent by
President Obasanjo to find a lasting solution to the ethnic
conflict in the area. 
</P>
</TEXT>
