<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nigerian Pipeline Vandalization Catches New </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, August 9 (Xinhua) -- Like a recurring vengeance, another
pipeline vandalization caused flames, killing at least one person
and hurting two in Mosogar, Nigeria's southern Delta State Sunday.
</P>
<P>
The accident took place in a place only a short stop from Jesse
of the state where about 1,000 residents died in a similar
pipeline fire on October 17 last year, the Guardian newspaper
reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
Three persons were known to have been hurt in the Mosogar fire
Sunday night. One identified as only Sabe was burnt beyond
recognition and was lying by a charred Mitsibushi bus near the
flaming pipeline, less than one kilometer from the vandalized pit
valve that caught fire at Jesse last year.
</P>
<P>
Two others, named James Eko and Aboki Eforie respectively, are
on admission at the Sapele Central Hospital, same place where many
victims of the Jesse fire were admitted last year.
</P>
<P>
Area Manager of the Petroleum Products Marketing Company,
Clement Okolie who raced to the scene Sunday, said that it was
another case of pipe vandalization.
</P>
<P>
Some 1,000 men, women and children who died in the Jesse fire
last year were killed from burns sustained while scooping petrol
from the vandalized pipeline.
</P>
<P>
Okolie said his company effected repairs to two vandalized
pipeline at Oghara and Jameson River creeks a few days ago, only
to be alerted Sunday of the problem at Mosagar.
</P>
<P>
"We only started pumping fuel Saturday. Now, we have to stop,"
said the irate manager. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
