<HEADLINE> Nigeria to Overhaul Health Care Scheme </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, August 9 (Xinhua) -- A rejuvenation of the proposed
Nigerian National Health Insurance Scheme (NHIS) will alleviate
health problems among Nigerians, Minister of State for Health
Aminat Ndalolo said Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Mdalolo, who described health as an expensive venture, however,
ruled out a national free health program on the grounds of
democratic immaturity, the Guardian newspaper reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
She said in eastern Kwara State at the weekend that existing
health programs in Nigeria would be overhauled within a month to
accommodate the downtrodden in the society.
</P>
<P>
According to the Kwara-born minister, even though the planned
health care scheme was initially conceived to take care of civil
servants and private workers, "we want to spread it to everybody,
including the poor masses."
</P>
<P>
She disclosed government's readiness to make available
sophisticated equipment and specialized medical personnel in order
to ensure smooth implementation of the scheme.
</P>
<P>
She also canvassed for the support of Nigerians to ensure the
success of the NHIS.
</P>
<P>
"Let me assure my fellow women in Kwara State in particular,
and the nation in general, that the (Olusegun) Obasanjo
administration is duly committed to improving our lot and giving
the Nigerian women equal opportunities like our male counterparts
in our collective drive to move the nation forward." 
</P>
