<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Putin: No Major Change of Russian Government Makeup </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, August 9 (Xinhua) -- Russia's newly appointed Prime
Minister, Vladimir Putin, said Monday that all key members of the
previous cabinet would keep their job.
</P>
<P>
"There will be no spontaneous dismissals or appointments," the
Interfax news agency quoted Putin as saying.
</P>
<P>
The 46-year-old former head of the Federal Security Service and
the Security Council replaced former prime minister Sergei
Stepashin in the fifth government sacking by President Boris
Yeltsin in one year and a half.
</P>
<P>
In a televised address to the nation, Yeltsin thanked Stepashin
for his "good work" in the past three months as premier and said
Putin is his preferred successor in the Kremlin.
</P>
<P>
Putin, in response, said he will "undoubtedly run" in the
presidential race scheduled for next June.
</P>
<P>
Yeltsin expressed his hope that the Russian electorate will
support Putin, whom he described as an individual capable of
consolidating the nation and ensuring the continuation of reforms.
</P>
<P>
"He is capable of uniting around himself those who in the new
21st century will face the task of renewing great Russia," Yeltsin
said.
</P>
<P>
"I am convinced that in this important capacity he will greatly
benefit the country, and Russians will have the opportunity to
appreciate Putin's human and professional qualities," Yeltsin
said. "I am confident in him, but I want everyone who goes to the
polling stations to make their choice in July 2000 to be confident
in him, too," Yeltsin said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Stepashin, a long-time Yeltsin loyalist, was offered
the post of secretary of the Security Council, a position Putin
had occupied since last March.
</P>
<P>
Stepashin was also presented with a number of alternative
proposals during his meeting with Yeltsin early Monday morning,
Interfax quoted sources close to Stepashin as saying.
</P>
<P>
However, the sources said that Stepashin "would not accept any
government jobs," noting that "this would be inexpedient in the
current, complex situation." 
</P>
</TEXT>
