<HEADLINE> Siberian Tiger Has Twin Cubs in Beijing Zoo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 9 (Xinhua) -- Jisheng, a 10-year-old Siberian
tiger, recently gave birth to twin cubs in the Beijing Zoo, her
third successful delivery in the past two years.
</P>
<P>
Jisheng gave birth to a litter of four cubs in May last year,
and veterinarians have been giving her special care and prescribed
food, which helped her to soon give birth again, in March this
year, before giving birth to the twin cubs at the end of July.
</P>
<P>
Jisheng was given the title "Heroine Mother Tiger" by her
guardians for her record of delivering 21 cubs in seven
pregnancies.
</P>
<P>
The two new tiger cubs each weigh over one kilogram and are
healthy and energetic.
</P>
<P>
Siberian tigers are generally larger than other tiger varieties,
and their number has been shrinking in recent years, putting them
on the list of the most protected animals in China.
</P>
<P>
Over 100 tigers of various kinds, including south China tigers
and Sumatran tigers, have been born in the Beijing Zoo, and the
first successful breeding of a Siberian tiger was in 1956.
nnnn
</P>
</TEXT>
