<HEADLINE> U.S. Interest Rates Rise No Big Threat to Thai Economy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, August 9 (Xinhua) -- The Thai economy is unlikely to
be seriously affected by the expected U.S. move of raising its
short-term interest rates, the official Thai News Agency (TNA)
quoted a senior official from Thailand's central bank as saying
Monday.
</P>
<P>
Kiattisak Meecharoen, Bank of Thailand's assistant governor,
was quoted by TNA as saying that the U.S. Federal Reserve Board
(FED) was expected to announce its decision to raise short-term
interest rates after its meeting on August 24.
</P>
<P>
The move, aiming to curb the upbeat of the U.S. economy, was
believed to have less effects on the Thai economy, as demand from
Thailand's other key trading partners, including Japan and the
European Union (EU), was still strong as their economies are
steadily reviving from the downturn, Kiattisak said.
</P>
<P>
The economic recovery of Thailand would not just depend on
exports and other factors, namely, domestic demand and increasing
consumers' purchasing power, also count, he said.
</P>
<P>
He said the Finance Ministry is creating an environment to
enhance consumers' demand and purchasing power through strategic
initiatives, while maintaining low interest rates to reduce
production costs and stimulate economic activities.
</P>
<P>
However, he admitted that the rising of U.S. interest rates
would somewhat lower Thailand's exports, like those of other
countries, as Washington is a key market for Thai exporters.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
