<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-09 12:13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Middle East Economic Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, August 9 (Xinhua) -- The following are economic briefs
from Middle East countries.
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- Egypt and Turkey have agreed to form a consortium
of world companies for the building of an Egyptian natural gas
pipeline to Turkey across the Mediterranean.
</P>
<P>
The two countries have also agreed to establish a maritime
transport line.
</P>
<P>
Representatives from the Turkish Potass Company and Egypt's
General Petroleum Authority would make technical and commercial
evaluation of the project.
</P>
<P>
Egypt plans to increase its natural gas exports to Turkey from
4 billion cubic meters annually to 8 billion cubic meters a year.
</P>
<P>
GAZA -- The Palestinian Monetary Authority has concluded a
feasibility study for the establishment of Palestinian Bank
for Housing and Development with a 50 million-dollar capital.
</P>
<P>
The bank is expected to start functioning later this year.
</P>
<P>
Authority Governor Fuad Bassiso told reporters Sunday that "the
project would be a joint venture with capital coming from various
quarters, including the Palestinian National Authority and the
group of banks operating in Palestine."
</P>
<P>
The bank will help boost banking activities in the Palestinian
self-rule areas, meet demands by the Palestinian people to
obtain loans, particularly in the field of housing, and to finance
diverse development projects.
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- A delegation of South Korea's Samsung Company is
due to arrive in Cairo on August 28 to sign an agreement with
Egypt's Maritime Shipyard Company for the building of giant ships
and floating hotels, the Arab daily Al Hayat reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
AMMAN -- The Jordanian government has decided to designate a
special railway line for the transportation of phosphate in a bid
to promote the country's phosphate exports.
</P>
<P>
The government entrusted a group of Jordanian and foreign
companies with the development of the railway line for a period of
25 years.
</P>
<P>
Jordan produces about six million tons of phosphate a year, the
principal raw material in the country. Production is due to rise
to 10 million tons by the year 2010, according to expert estimates.
</P>
</TEXT>
