<HEADLINE> 5 Injured as Goods Train Derails in Northeast India </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, August 9 (Xinhua) -- Seven wagons and the engine of
a goods train derailed in a powerful bomb explosion early Monday
morning in Assam, northeastern India, injuring five people.
</P>
<P>
As a result of the explosion around 2:10 a.m. local time in
Kokrajhar district of Assam, five of the derailed wagons capsized
into the nullah below a culvert bridge, which was allegedly blown
up by suspected militants, the Press Trust of India (PTI)
reported.
</P>
<P>
The engine driver of the train was seriously wounded while the
assistant driver and three people of the Railway Protection
Security Force inside the engine also sustained injuries, the PTI
said, quoting railway sources.
</P>
<P>
The sources said that the target of the explosion could have
been a passenger express which was scheduled to cross the bridge
an hour later.
</P>
<P>
This is the third rail accident this month in India.
</P>
<P>
On August 2, two trains collided in the northern area of West
Bengal, killing at least 290 passengers and forcing Railway
Minister Nitish Kumar to resign for his "moral" responsibility.
</P>
<P>
On the same day, an explosion in a crowded local train in the
west state of Maharashtra left one dead and five injured. 
</P>
</TEXT>
