<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Africa Urged to Develop Communications System </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, August 9 (Xinhua) -- African countries have been urged
to make efforts to develop an efficient and continent-wide
transport and communications system.
</P>
<P>
Zambian Minister of Foreign Affairs Keli Walubita said here
Monday that an efficient and continent-wide transport and
communications system is vital to improving the Africa's
competitive edge in the global economy.
</P>
<P>
The minister made the call at a luncheon in honor of Kingsiey
Amoako, Undersecretary-General of the United Nations and the
Executive Secretary of the Economic Commission for Africa (ECA).
</P>
<P>
Walubita said that the provision of infrastructure services is
also central to poverty reduction. The lack of access to
infrastructure is a real welfare issue, particularly in the rural
areas where poverty is most predominant.
</P>
<P>
Adequate infrastructure such as feeder roads, access to safe
drinking water and sanitation, electrification and irrigation, is
essential to successful rural transformation and agricultural
development, he said.
</P>
<P>
The Economic Commission for Africa has an important role to
play in Africa's development in the economic, social and
environmental spheres, said Walubita.
</P>
<P>
The ECA played a pivotal role in the establishment of the
preferential trade area for east and southern African states
(PTA), which has now been transformed into the Common Market for
East and Southern African States (COMESA), the largest economic
integration grouping in Africa.
</P>
<P>
The minister further noted that Africa cannot hope to benefit
from open regionalism without the involvement of the ECA.
</P>
<P>
The ECA should also promote international cooperation for
African debt relief, he noted.
</P>
<P>
Amoako is in Zambia for a four-day visit to the country and he
will hold talks with officials of the COMESA during the visit.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
