<BODY>
<HEADLINE> No Plans to Regulate Gold Imports: Indian Minister </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, August 9 (Xinhua) -- India Monday ruled out any move
to regulate gold imports in the wake of a sharp increase in the
flow of the yellow metal from abroad in recent months.
</P>
<P>
"Under the present policy, gold imports are permitted. So you
can not prevent people from importing," Finance Minister Yashwant
Sinha told reporters here Monday.
</P>
<P>
With continued decline of gold prices in the global market,
India's gold imports shot up 230 percent to 80 tons in June from
24 tons recorded in the same month last year.
</P>
<P>
Gold imports went down in India in the first few months of the
current financial year, allegedly for the increase of duty the
finance minister had brought about in his budget in April, the
first month of the financial year.
</P>
<P>
According to the Reserve Bank of India, during the first
quarter of the current fiscal year, gold imports stood at 187
tons, 32 percent higher than the 142 tons recorded a year earlier.
</P>
<P>
India is a major gold importer in the world. The country
imported 736 tons of gold in 1997 and 185 tons of gold in 1998.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
