<DOCNO> XIE19990809.0229 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. Africa Says Talks on Congo Peace Fruitful </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, August 9 (Xinhua) -- Talks between South African
President Thabo Mbeki and his counterparts from Rwanda, Uganda and
Tanzania on the conflict in the Democratic Republic of Congo (DRC)
were "fruitful", South African Foreign Ministry said Monday.
</P>
<P>
President Pasteur Bizimungu of Rwanda, Yoweri Museveni of
Uganda and Benjamin Mkapa of Tanzania met in Pretoria on Sunday
evening for another round of shuttle diplomacy aimed at finalizing
the July 10 Lusaka cease- fire agreement that would end the
year-long war in the Congo.
</P>
<P>
South African Press Association quoted Foreign Ministry
spokesman Daniel Ngwepe as saying that the "verification process"
of the peace deal would continue with South African Foreign
Minister Nkosazana Zuma expected to travel to Congo's northeastern
city of Kisangani Tuesday with a Zambian delegation led by
Zambia's Minister for Presidential Affairs, Eric Silwamba.
</P>
<P>
They are supposed to hold talks with leaders of the Congolese
Rally for Democracy (RCD), the main rebel movement fighting to
overthrow Congolese President Laurent Kabila.
</P>
<P>
The RCD split into two rival factions on May 19 this year. Now
both factions claimed they have the right to sign the Lusaka
accord already inked by the other players in the conflict.
</P>
<P>
The rebel Congo Liberation Movement (MLC) and six countries
directly involved in the war have signed the document, but the
fractured RCD cannot agree on which faction should sign the
cease-fire accord.
</P>
<P>
Rwanda and Uganda are believed to back different factions of
the RCD.
</P>
<P>
The main faction of the RCD, headed by Emile Illunga, is based
in Congo's eastern town of Goma and has Rwandan support, while the
other is run from Kisangani with backing from Uganda by Ernest
Wamba dia Wamba. 
</P>
</TEXT>
