<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Vice-Premier Meets Overseas Chinese Youth Delegation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 9 (Xinhua)-- Chinese Vice-Premier Li Lanqing
met with a delegation from the China Synergy Program for
Outstanding Youth, headed by Chang Hsin-kang, president of the
City University of Hong Kong, here today.
</P>
<P>
Li, also a member of the Standing Committee of the Political
Bureau of the Chinese Communist Party Central Committee, said that
China is now at an important juncture when it is carrying forward
the cause pioneered by its revolutionary predecessors and forging
ahead into the future.
</P>
<P>
Over the past 50 years, particularly in the 20 years since the
policies of reform and opening were introduced, China has found a
way to build socialism with Chinese characteristics, he said.
China is now deepening its economic restructuring, with its
national strength continuing to grow, and the people's living
standard keeps improving.
</P>
<P>
Li said that over the past two years the Hong Kong Special
Administrative Region has successfully implemented the principle
of "One Country, Two Systems". Macao will also return to the
motherland late this year, the vice-premier said. "We have the
determination, the capability and confidence to ultimately settle
the Taiwan issue and realize reunification."
</P>
<P>
Li also briefed the visitors on China's strategy of
revitalizing the country through education and science, and the on-
going reform in higher education and science and technology.
</P>
<P>
Li said that the visit of the delegation will enlarge the
knowledge of overseas Chinese about China. Li also invited them to
contribute to the development of the mainland.
</P>
<P>
Wang Zhaoguo, vice-chairman of the national committee of the
Chinese People's Political Consultative Conference (CPPCC), was
present at the meeting.
</P>
<P>
Also today, Jia Qinglin, secretary of the Beijing Municipal
Chinese Communist Party Committee, met with the delegation.
</P>
<P>
Jia said the visit by the delegation will expand exchanges
between young people in Beijing and overseas. He briefed the
delegation members on the situation of Beijing's urban
construction and economic development, and the preparations for
the celebration of the 50th anniversary of the founding of the
People's Republic of China, on October 1 this year.
</P>
<P>
Organized by leading figures in Hong Kong, the delegation is
composed of overseas Chinese students from famous universities.
</P>
<P>
The delegation visited historical sites in Beijing and had
discussions with local youngsters. The delegation will leave for
Shanghai after winding up its visit to Beijing.  
</P>
</TEXT>
