<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, August 9 (Xinhua) -- Ugandan President Yoweri Museveni
has come back home from a short working visit to South Africa
during which he held talks with his counterparts from Tanzania,
Rwanda and the host country on the Congo issue.
</P>
<P>
The talks took place Sunday afternoon at the Presidential Guest
House in Pretoria and continued well into the night, a press
release from the President's Office said here Monday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
During their discussions, the four leaders reviewed the
progress made so far in the peace process in the Democratic
Republic of Congo (DRC) and exchanged views and ideas about how to
advance that process even further.
</P>
<P>
Uganda and Rwanda are said to have been urged to persuade
rebels in the Congo to sign the Lusaka cease-fire agreement.
Lately, there have been signs of breaking of the accord, posing
the most serious threat to the fragile peace process in the vast
central African country.
</P>
<P>
There have been reports that rebels backed by the Rwandan
government exchanged fire with Ugandan troops deployed in
northeastern Congo Saturday and casualties were reported on both
sides.
</P>
<P>
Uganda and Rwanda are said to have backed one of the two
factions each, after the main rebel group Congolese Rally for
Democracy split into two factions in mid-May this year. 
</P>
