<HEADLINE> Canada Asked to Help Afghanistan Build Infrastructure </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, August 9 (Xinhua) -- Afghan Taliban militia have
asked Canada to help construct highways and airports as well as
laying railway lines, the News Network International said Monday.
</P>
<P>
A Canadian team recently visited the Afghan capital of Kabul
and held in-depth talks with Taliban officials on the construction
of highways, airports, roads, railway lines and other projects in
the war-torn country.
</P>
<P>
The Canadian team will soon conduct a survey and prepare a
feasibility report, the report said.
</P>
<P>
The report quoted Muhammad Naeem, an official of Afghanistan's
Bakhtar news agency, as saying that the railway project will be
initiated after holding further talks with the Taliban.
</P>
<P>
Afghanistan has no railway lines and all previous efforts to
have the facility have failed. In the 1970s, a project to lay
railway lines was initiated with the financial support of some
Arab states and Iran. However, it was abandoned with the topple of
the Dawood government.
</P>
<P>
It is still not known who will fund the proposed railway line
project between Canada and Afghanistan. 
</P>
