<HEADLINE> Natural Gas Prices at 15-year Peak in Canada </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, August 9 (Xinhua) -- Canada's natural gas prices are
soaring and at a 15-year peak this summer, with consumers facing
an extra charge of up to 5.00 Canadian dollars (about 3.30 U.S.
dollars) a month, the Globe and Mail newspaper reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
Industry prices for Alberta natural gas have almost doubled
over last August's average, rising 40 percent in the past five
months and jumping past the important 3.00 Canadian dollar (about
1.99 U.S. dollars) barrier the newspaper said.
</P>
<P>
Although price increases are normal for winter heating bills,
it is quite unusual that natural gas prices are up in summer when
warm weather reduces demand from businesses and homes, according
to the newspaper.
</P>
<P>
Industry experts said a combination of factors have created
this summer's rising market.
</P>
<P>
Current tight gas supplies across western Canada and the
prospect of growing demand from the United States this coming
winter have contributed to the unusual mid-year surge, the
newspaper quoted a senior gas-supply planning engineer Timo
Makinen as saying.
</P>
<P>
Other factors resulting in the price hike include a shortage of
gas drilling this year and a heat wave in many parts of North
America, where people used gas-operated air conditioners, the
newspaper added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
