<HEADLINE> Japan to Closely Follow Situation in Russia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, August 9 (Xinhua) -- Japan voiced concern Monday over
the political uncertainty in Russia after Russian President Boris
Yeltsin dismissed Prime Minister Sergei Stepashin and his cabinet
earlier in the day.
</P>
<P>
The Japanese government will "closely follow developments" in
Russia to determine the impact of the renewed turbulence, Chief
Cabinet Secretary Hiromu Nonaka told a press conference.
</P>
<P>
But Nonaka expressed confidence that Yeltsin will overcome
Russia's fresh political turmoil and proceed with reform efforts.
</P>
<P>
"We are confident that President Yeltsin will exert his
leadership to overcome various problems under the big wave of
reforms and democratization," the top government spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
Earlier Monday Yeltsin sacked Stepashin and his cabinet and
named Vladimir Putin, secretary of the advisory Security Council,
as acting premier.
</P>
<P>
It was the fourth time in 18 months that Yeltsin dismissed his
prime minister. The move came less than three months after Yeltsin
sacked the former Prime Minister Yevgeny Primakov and named
Stepashin as successor.
</P>
<P>
Nonaka said Japan remained committed to "continuing to
strengthen cooperation and improve relations with Russia."
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Japanese Vice Foreign Minister Shunji Yanai told a
separate press conference that Japan "is closely following
developments...and gathering information" to determine the fate of
the planned top-level consultations between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
Tokyo and Moscow have been working to set Yeltsin's official
visit to Japan this fall in a bid to boost bilateral relations.
</P>
<P>
They have also been arranging a meeting between Japanese Prime
Minister Keizo Obuchi and Stepashin on the sidelines of the annual
informal summit of the Asia-Pacific Economic Cooperation forum,
slated for September 12-13 in New Zealand.
</P>
<P>
Russian political uncertainty has repeatedly frustrated Japan
in its bid to resolve a long-standing territorial row and realize
a peace treaty with Russia by the end of next year, as the two
countries earlier pledged. 
</P>
</TEXT>
