<HEADLINE> HK Customs Seizes "Ice" Worth 2.8 Million HK Dollars </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, August 9 (Xinhua) -- The Hong Kong Customs cracked
down an international drug smuggling syndicate following the
seizure of 5.1 kilograms of suspected methylamphetamine "ice" at
the airport Monday morning.
</P>
<P>
The drugs, worth about 2.8 million HK dollars (359,000 U.S.
dollars), were found on two Indonesian men, who hid the five
packages of "ice" around their waists by adhesive tapes.
</P>
<P>
Customs officers from the Drug Investigation Bureau (CDIB)
intercepted the two at the departure lounge when they were
departing for Jakarta.
</P>
<P>
The arrested men, aged between 42 and 45, will be charged with
"trafficking in a dangerous drug" and will appear in Tsuen Wan
Magistracy Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Since January 1999, Airport Customs has detected 16 drug cases
on incoming and outgoing passengers. The seized drugs included 23
kilograms of heroin, 12,942 tablets of ecstasy, 1.1 kilograms of
cocaine and 8.2 kilograms of "ice". 
</P>
