<HEADLINE> Iran Releases Two Detained Turkish Soldiers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, August 9 (Xinhua) -- Iran released the two detained
Turkish soldiers Monday in a bid to ease the tension between the
two countries, the semi-official Anatolia News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
The pair were handed over to a Turkish delegation formed by
Baskale town Governor Sevket Cinbir and Colonel Halil Ibrahim
Yaman at the Kapikoy Border Gendarme Station in Saray town in
Turkey's eastern province of Van.
</P>
<P>
The agency said that the pair were detained for entering
the Iranian territory on July 22.
</P>
<P>
Iran has promised to let the pair go before the sixth meeting
of the Turkey-Iran Higher Council on Security, which is scheduled
to be held in Ankara on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Local Hurriyet (Freedom) daily has said that Iran's release of
the two soldiers will show a "sign of goodwill" to Turkey.
</P>
<P>
Turkey has told Iran at recent meetings between the two
countries that the continued detention of the two Turkish soldiers
was creating unwanted tension in bilateral relations.
</P>
<P>
Ties between the two countries were strained after Iran claimed
that Turkish warplanes attacked an Iranian military post and tents
belonging to Iranian tribesmen on July 18, during which five
people were killed and 10 others injured.
</P>
<P>
Turkey has said that the attack was aimed at the outlawed
Kurdish Workers' Party (PKK), which uses bases in northern Iraq
for hit-and-run attacks on Turkish territory.
</P>
<P>
Turkey has complained that Iran allowed the PKK rebels to move
into the Iranian territory and then the rebels often entered the
Turkish territory to launch attacks against the Turkish military
and civilian targets.
</P>
<P>
The PKK has been fighting since 1984 a war for an independent
Kurdish state in southeastern Turkey. Conflicts between the
Turkish security forces and the PKK militants have claimed over
37,000 lives. 
</P>
</TEXT>
