<HEADLINE> India Rules Out Early Resumption of Talks With Pakistan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, August 9 (Xinhua) -- India Monday ruled out an early
resumption of bilateral talks with Pakistan so long as
"cross-border terrorism" sponsored by Islamabad continued.
</P>
<P>
"We wish to resume the Lahore process" which started last
February when then Indian Prime Minister Atal Behari Vajpayee took
bus to the Pakistani city of Lahore, and the composite dialogue
which followed, a spokesman of the External Affairs Ministry told
the press here Monday.
</P>
<P>
However, he added, "Pakistan must facilitate the creation of an
atmosphere conducive to such resumption by abandoning the path of
hostility and confrontation and its state terrorism against
India."
</P>
<P>
Pakistan's High Commissioner in New Delhi Ashraf Jehangir Qazi
proposed Sunday a meeting with Indian leaders during the United
Nations General Assembly session in New York next month, saying
the stalled dialogue process should not be held hostage by the
election campaign scheduled in September in India.
</P>
<P>
But the Indian spokesman denied any knowledge of the proposal,
saying that for the present there was no proposal for a meeting at
the political level during the forthcoming U.N. General Assembly.
</P>
<P>
Reports from Islamabad said that Pakistani Foreign Minister
Sartaj Aziz also dismissed the possibility of the resumption of
dialogue between the two neighbors during the U.N. session.
</P>
<P>
"The session is being held at a time when India will be busy
with general elections and there will be no government in New
Delhi, how can talks be possible in this scenario?" Aziz
reportedly told a mass-circulated daily.
</P>
<P>
The Indian spokesman repeated the three preconditions for the
resumption of talks with Pakistan put forward before the end of
the latest conflict in Kashmir, emphasizing that "in any event the
real issue is the need for Pakistan to respect the inviolability
and sanctity of the Line of Control (LoC)," the de facto border
between the two sides.
</P>
<P>
"The continuance of cross-border terrorism is a clear violation
of the LoC and must cease forthwith," he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
