<HEADLINE> International Day of World's Indigenous People  Marked at U.N. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, August 9 (Xinhua) -- The International Day of
World's Indigenous people, which falls on Monday, is celebrated at
the United Nations headquarters in New York with two days of
workshops and events, including a cultural event paying tribute to
indigenous human rights defender, a Sacred Pipe Ceremony and the
official opening of an exhibit of Australian Aboriginal art.
</P>
<P>
Topics for the workshops include the relationship of indigenous
peoples to land and how indigenous peoples can lobby governments.
</P>
<P>
Indigenous peoples from around the world will gather for the
events, which are open to the public here.
</P>
<P>
The International Day of the World's Indigenous People is an
opportunity for indigenous peoples and groups, working together
with other interested parties, to organize activities which raise
awareness about indigenous peoples, their history, their cultures,
their aspirations and their contemporary concerns. U.N. officials
said.
</P>
<P>
It was first proclaimed by the United Nations General Assembly
in 1994 to be observed each year during the International Decade
of the World's Indigenous People (1995-2004).
</P>
<P>
It is estimated that there are at least 5,000 indigenous groups
composed of 300 million people living in more than 70 countries on
five continents. Their way of life, livelihood, religion and
culture are inextricably interwined with and dependent on the
traditional environment in which they live, the officials said.
</P>
<P>
In many parts of the world, the cultures of indigenous peoples
are precariously balanced on the edge of extinction, the officials
added.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
