<HEADLINE> Bangladeshi Policemen Issue With U.N. Should Be Taken Seriously: FM </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, August 9 (Xinhua) -- The Bangladeshi government has
asked the country's permanent mission at the United Nations to
take up the matter of its police contingent sent to Kosovo with
the concerned UN officials, Foreign Minister Abdus Samad Azad said
here Monday.
</P>
<P>
"Our permanent representative has been asked to take up the
matter seriously," Azad told newsmen, referring to press reports
which said Bangladeshi policemen who went to Kosovo to take up the
"peace assignment" are being sent back for their failure to pass
certain tests.
</P>
<P>
Azad reiterated that till Monday his ministry has not been
officially informed by the U.N. of anything regarding the reported
sending back of Bangladeshi policemen from Kosovo. "What we have
come to know on the matter is all unofficial," he asserted.
</P>
<P>
Forty-nine Bangladeshi policemen experienced in the U.N.
peacekeeping mission were recruited in the contingent after they
fulfilled all the U.N. specifications of their recruitment in the
peacekeeping job, and they were sent to Kosovo on July 27.
</P>
<P>
Bangladesh, which has been taking part in U.N. peace missions
since the late 1980s, has so far sent a few thousand troops and
policemen who had already completed their 16 peace missions.
</P>
<P>
Of the eight U.N. peace missions currently in operation,
Bangladeshi policemen have been assigned in three places --
Bosnia, East Timor and Kosovo. And earlier, Bangladeshi policemen
served in U.N. peace missions in Angola, Cambodia, Haiti,
Mozambique, Namibia and Rwanda. 
</P>
</TEXT>
