<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.N., E. Timor Police Sign Accord on Poll Security </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, August 9 (Xinhua) -- The U.N. civil police in East
Timor and the local police Monday concluded an agreement to handle
security in the run-up to and during the U.N.-administered
autonomy ballot on the territory's political future by the end of
August.
</P>
<P>
The agreement was signed by East Timor Police Chief Col. Timbul
Silaen and U.N. Civil Police Commissioner Alan Mills in Dili,
capital of East Timor, according to the Antara News Agency.
</P>
<P>
Under the agreement, the U.N. civil police would provide advice
to the local police relevant to the consultation process.
</P>
<P>
On the other hand, the East Timor police, as the sole
institution responsible for the maintenance of security in the
territory, is expected to consider seriously whatever advice given
by the U.N. police.
</P>
<P>
The agreement also requires the U.N. police to be neutral while
providing advice fairly and carrying out duties in line with the
tripartite agreement singed by U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan
and Indonesian and Portuguese foreign ministers.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. civil police could not directly or indirectly carry
out the Indonesian police's jobs such as investigation, detaining
a person or other activities related to the upholding of law and
public order.
</P>
<P>
The United Nations is organizing a direct ballot in East Timor
to enable the East Timorese to accept or reject a wide-ranging
autonomy offered by the Indonesian government early this year.
</P>
<P>
A rejection of the autonomy proposal will mean independence for
the former Portuguese colony.
</P>
<P>
East Timor was integrated into Indonesia in 1976, a move never
recognized by the United Nations. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
